web.archive.org/web/20140117042641/http://www.irishpennsylvania.com/ Irish Pennsylvania]\n\n{{European Americans}}\n{{Demographics of the United States}}\n{{Irish Americans by location}}\n{{Irish diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent| ]]\n[[Category:Irish American|*]]\n[[Category:Irish-American history| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Irish Americans<br />''Gael-Mheirice\u00e1naigh''\n| image = Irish_ancestry_in_the_USA_and_Canada.png\n| image_caption = <div style=\"text-align: center>Irish Americans and Irish Canadians, % of population by state or province</div>\n| caption = Notable Irish Americans\n| population = '''Self-identified \"Irish\"'''<br />'''32,562,619'''<ref name=\"ACS 2013\u201317 5Y Estimate\" /><br /><small>10.1% of the US population (2017)</small><br />\n| popplace = [[Boston]] {{\u2022}} [[New York City]] {{\u2022}} [[Philadelphia]] {{\u2022}} [[Atlanta]]  {{\u2022}} [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] {{\u2022}} [[Chicago]] {{\u2022}} [[New England]] {{\u2022}} [[Delaware Valley]] {{\u2022}} most urban areas<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/trulia/2013/03/15/americas-most-irish-towns/amp/ |title=America's Most Irish Towns |magazine=Forbes}}</ref>\n| langs = [[English language|English]] <small>([[American English|American English dialects]])</small>; minority can speak [[Irish language|Irish]]\n| rels = [[Protestantism in the United States|Protestant]] (51%) {{\u2022}} [[Irish Catholics|Catholic]] (36%) {{\u2022}} [[Religion in the United States|Other]] (3%) {{\u2022}} [[Irreligion in the United States|No religion]] (10%) (2006)<ref>{{cite journal|last=Carroll|first=Michael P.|title=How the Irish Became Protestant in America|journal=[[Religion and American Culture]]|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=Winter 2006|volume=16|issue=1|pages=25\u201354|jstor=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25|doi=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25}}</ref>\n| related = [[Anglo-Irish people]] {{\u2022}} [[Breton Americans]] {{\u2022}} [[Cornish Americans]] {{\u2022}} [[English Americans]] {{\u2022}} [[Irish Australians]] {{\u2022}} [[Irish Canadians]] {{\u2022}} [[Irish Catholics]] {{\u2022}} [[Manx Americans]] {{\u2022}} [[Scotch-Irish Americans]] {{\u2022}} [[Scottish Americans]] {{\u2022}} [[Scottish Canadians]] {{\u2022}} [[Ulster Protestants]] {{\u2022}} [[Ulster Scots people]] {{\u2022}} [[Welsh Americans]]\n}}\n{{Bar chart\n| title = Number of Irish Americans \n| label_type = Year\n| data_type = Number\n| bar_width = 15\n| width_units = em\n| data_max = 55,163,702\n| float = right\n| label1 = 1980<ref>{{cite web|title=Rank of States for Selected Ancestry Groups with 100,000 or more persons: 1980|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/censusdata/files/pc80-s1-10/tab04.pdf|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> \n| data1 = 40,165,702\n| label2 = 1990<ref>{{cite web|title=1990 Census of Population Detailed Ancestry Groups for States|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/cen1990/cp-s/cp-s-1-2.pdf|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=30 November 2012|date=18 September 1992}}</ref> \n| data2 = 38,735,539 \n| label3 = 2000<ref>{{cite web|title=Ancestry: 2000|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_00_SF3_QTP13&prodType=table|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212213043/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_00_SF3_QTP13&prodType=table|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 February 2020|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> \n| data3 = 30,528,492\n| label4 = 2010<ref>{{cite web|title=Total ancestry categories tallied for people with one or more ancestry categories reported 2010 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_10_1YR_B04003&prodType=table|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150118121537/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_10_1YR_B04003&prodType=table|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 January 2015|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> \n| data4 = 34,670,009\n}}\n\n'''Irish Americans''' ({{lang-ga|Gael-Mheirice\u00e1naigh}}) are an ethnic group comprising Americans who have full or partial ancestry from [[Ireland]]. About 33 million Americans \u2014 10.1% of the total population \u2014 self-identified as being of Irish ancestry in the 2017 [[American Community Survey]] conducted by the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]].<ref name=\"ACS 2013\u201317 5Y Estimate\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_13_5YR_DP03&prodType=table|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150117113227/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_13_5YR_DP03&prodType=table|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 17, 2015|title=B04006 \u2013 PEOPLE REPORTING SINGLE ANCESTRY 2013-2017 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]]|access-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref> This compares with a population of 6.8 million on the island of Ireland. In contrast to Ireland, surveys since the 1970s have shown consistent majorities or pluralities of Americans who self-identify as being of Irish ancestry as also self-identifying as being [[Protestantism in the United States|Protestant]],<ref name=\"Carroll 2006 p. 25\">{{cite journal|last=Carroll|first=Michael P.|title=How the Irish Became Protestant in America|journal=[[Religion and American Culture]]|volume=16|issue=1|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|doi=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25|year=2006|page=25}}</ref><ref name=\"RNS 3-17-2014\">{{cite article|title=St. Patrick's Day Graph: Irish in America are Protestant, not Catholic|date=March 17, 2014|publisher=[[Religion News Service]]|url=https://religionnews.com/2014/03/17/irish-americans-religion-politics/|access-date=June 2, 2019}}</ref> and are actually mostly [[Scotch-Irish Americans|Scotch-Irish]],<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. x\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The Irish Americans: A History|page=x|year=2008|isbn=978-1596914193|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]|quote=The term [Scotch-Irish] had been in use during the eighteenth century to designate Ulster Presbyterians who had emigrated to the United States. From the mid-1700s through the early 1800s, however, the term Irish was more widely used to identify both Catholic and Protestant Irish... as political and religious conflict between Catholics and Protestants both in Ireland and the United States became more frequent, and as Catholic emigrants began to outnumber Protestants, the term Irish became synonymous with Irish Catholics. As a result, Scotch-Irish became the customary term to describe Protestants of Irish descent... The famine migration of the 1840s and '50s that sent waves of poor Irish Catholics to the United States together with the rise in anti-Catholicism intensified this attitude. In no way did Irish Protestants want to be identified with these ragged newcomers.}}</ref><ref name=\"Webb p. 15\">{{cite book|first=Jim|last=Webb|author-link=Jim Webb|title=Born Fighting: How the Scots-Irish Shaped America|publisher=[[Broadway Books]]|year=2004|page=[https://archive.org/details/bornfightinghows00webb/page/15 15]|isbn=978-0767916899|title-link=Born Fighting}}</ref> the American descendants of [[Ulster Protestants]] (mostly [[Ulster Scots people|Ulster Scots]]) who emigrated from Ireland to the United States en masse from the early 18th century through the early 1920s.<ref name=\"Jones 1980 pp. 896\u2013908\">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Maldwyn A.|year=1980|chapter=Scotch-Irish|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/896 896\u2013908]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/904}}</ref>\n\nThree million people separately self-identified as Scotch-Irish,<ref name=\"ACS 2013\u201317 5Y Estimate\" /> but demographers have long assumed the U.S. Census Bureau self-identification estimate of the Scotch-Irish to be a serious undercount (in part, because along with [[English Americans|English]] and other [[British Americans|British]] ancestries, many Scotch-Irish self-identify as being of \"[[American ancestry]]\").<ref name=\"Pulera2004\">{{cite book|author=Dominic Pulera|title=Sharing the Dream: White Males in Multicultural America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SVoAXh-dNuYC&pg=PA57|date= 2004|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-0-8264-1643-8|pages=57\u201360}}</ref><ref name=\"Barkan2013\">{{cite book|author=Elliott Robert Barkan|title=Immigrants in American History: Arrival, Adaptation, and Integration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AP7QCteb0o0C&pg=PA791|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-219-7|pages=791\u2013}}</ref> While some argue that the Scotch-Irish should be considered Irish,<ref>{{cite book|last=Leyburn|first=James G.|title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History|url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb|url-access=registration|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|place=[[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill, NC]]|year=1962|isbn=978-0807842591|page=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/327 327]}}</ref> considering that conversions by [[Irish Catholics]] during the [[Reformation in Ireland]] to [[Protestantism in Ireland|Protestant churches]] were historically rare,<ref name=\"Duffy p. 100\u2013107\">{{cite book|last=Duffy|first=Sean|title=The Concise History of Ireland|publisher=[[Gill (publisher)|Gill & MacMillan]]|isbn=978-0717138104|pages=100\u2013107|year=2005|quote=...the Irish saw the Protestant Reformation as just an instrument of military conquest and forced Anglicisation... [because of this] the numbers of Roman Catholics remained high [during Queen Elizabeth's reign] and they were zealously ministered to by a plentiful supply of Continentally-trained priests, among whom the Jesuits were predominant: the latter were so successful in performing their task that by the end of Elizabeth's reign they had won the hearts-and-minds battle among the populace, as regards the choice between Catholicism and Protestantism... [By] 1603... it was too late and the Protestant Reformation had failed in Ireland.}}</ref> and that intermarriage between Protestants and Catholics in both Ireland and in the United States was also historically rare{{refn|group=list|name=US&IrelandIntermarriage2|<ref name=\"Robinson p. 111\">{{cite book |last=Robinson|first=Philip S.|title=The Plantation of Ulster: British Settlement in an Irish Landscape, 1600-1670|edition=2nd|publisher=Ulster Historical Foundation|orig-year=1984 |year=2000 |isbn=978-1903688007|page=111|quote=...many English did not conform to the Established Church, and there has been relatively less social resistance to intermarriage between Protestants of differing denominations than between Protestants and Roman Catholics.}}</ref><ref name=\"Fischer p. 620\">{{cite book |first=David Hackett|last=Fischer|author-link=David Hackett Fischer|year=1989|title=Albion's Seed: Four British Folkways in America|place=New York|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |page=620 |isbn=978-0195069051|quote=In the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, it was observed that 'the Ulster settlers mingled freely with the English Puritans and Huguenots,' but married very rarely with the Gaelic-speaking people of Ireland and Scotland.|title-link=Albion's Seed}}</ref><ref name=\"Leyburn pp. 133\u2013139\" /><ref name=\"Dunaway pp. 9\u201311\" /><ref name=\"Fernihough, O'Grada & Walsh 2015\">{{cite journal |last1=Fernihough |first1=Alan |last2=O'Grada |first2=Cormac|last3=Walsh|first3=Brendan M.|title=Intermarriage in a Divided Society: Ireland a Century Ago |journal=[[Explorations in Economic History]]|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|year=April 2015|volume=56|pages=1\u201314|url=https://pure.qub.ac.uk/portal/files/13821188/queenswp.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.eeh.2014.11.002}}</ref><ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 228\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/228 228]}}</ref>}} while [[Interethnic marriage|interethnic]] and [[Interfaith marriage in Christianity|interdenominational marriage]] amongst [[Protestantism in Ireland|Protestants]] in [[Ulster]] was relatively common,{{refn|group=list|name=IrelandProtestantinterethnic&interdenominationalmarriage2|<ref name=\"Robinson p. 111\" /><ref name=\"Robinson p. 113\">{{cite book |last=Robinson |first=Philip S. |title=The Plantation of Ulster: British Settlement in an Irish Landscape, 1600-1670 |edition=2nd |publisher=Ulster Historical Foundation |orig-year=1984 |year=2000 |isbn=978-1903688007 |page=113 |quote=Areas of English settlement in County Londonderry, north Armagh, south-west Antrim and Fermanagh support the assumption that most non-Presbyterian British were of English stock. In places these 'English' settlers included Welsh and Manx men.}}</ref><ref name=\"Miller et. al 2003 p. 13\">{{cite book |last1=Miller |first1=Kerby A. |author-link1=Kerby A. Miller |last2=Schrier |first2=Arnold |last3=Boling |first3=Bruce D. |last4=Doyle |first4=David N. |title=Irish Immigrants in the Land of Canaan: Letters and Memoirs from Colonial and Revolutionary America, 1675\u20131815 |year=2003 |place=New York |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |page=13 |isbn=978-0195045130 |quote=In the 1650s perhaps as many as 30,000 English and Welsh Protestants migrated across the Irish Sea.}}</ref><ref name=\"Leyburn p. 128\">{{cite book |last=Leyburn |first=James G. |title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History |url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb |url-access=registration |publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]] |orig-year=1962 |year=1989 |edition=reprint |page=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/128 128] |isbn=978-0807842591}}</ref><ref name=\"Fischer p. 620\" />}} multiple historians have argued instead that the \"Scotch-Irish\" distinction remains necessary as the [[Ulster Protestants]] remain a distinct [[ethnoreligious group]] from the [[Irish Catholics]].{{refn|group=list|name=linguisticretention|<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. x\" /><ref name=\"Leyburn p. 333\" /><ref name=\"Dunaway p. 7\" />}}\n\n{{TOC limit|4}}\n\n==Irish immigration to the United States==\n{{Main|Irish diaspora}}\n{{See also|Irish Catholics|Ulster Protestants|Ulster Scots people|Anglo-Irish people}}\n\n===17th to mid-19th century===\n{{Main|Scotch-Irish Americans|Irish indentured servants|Great Famine (Ireland)}}\n{{See also|Irish slaves myth}}\n\n{{multiple image\n |align    = right\n |width    = 175\n |direction= vertical\n |image1   = Scotch Irish or American ancestry by county.png\n |caption1 = U.S. counties by the percentage of their population self-identifying [[Scotch-Irish Americans|Scotch-Irish]] or [[American ancestry]] according to the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]] [[American Community Survey]] 2013\u20132017 5-Year Estimates.<ref name=\"ACS 2013\u201317 5Y Estimate\" /> Counties where Scotch-Irish and American ancestry combined are greater than the United States as a whole are in full orange.\n |image2   = Irish ancestry by state.png\n |caption2 = U.S. states by the percentage of their population self-identifying Irish ancestry according to the U.S. Census Bureau.<ref name=\"ACS 2013\u201317 5Y Estimate\" /> States where Irish ancestry is greater than the United States as a whole are in full green.\n |image3   = Irish Catholics by state.png\n |caption3 = U.S. states where self-identified Irish Americans are overrepresented by the percentage of self-identified [[Catholic Church in the United States|Catholics]] according to the [[Pew Research Center]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Catholics - Religion in America: U.S. Religious Data, Demographics and Statistics|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|url=https://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/religious-tradition/catholic/|access-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref> States where the percentage of Catholics is greater than the United States as a whole are in full red.\n |image4   = Irish Protestants by state.png\n |caption4 = U.S. states where self-identified Irish Americans are overrepresented by the percentage of self-identified [[Protestantism in the United States|Protestants]] ([[Evangelicalism in the United States|Evangelical]] or [[Mainline Protestant|Mainline]]) according to the Pew Research Center.<ref>{{cite web|title=Evangelical Protestants - Religion in America: U.S. Religious Data, Demographics and Statistics|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|url=https://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/religious-tradition/evangelical-protestant/|access-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mainline Protestants - Religion in America: U.S. Religious Data, Demographics and Statistics|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|url=https://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/religious-tradition/mainline-protestant/|access-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref> States where the percentage of Protestants is greater than the United States as a whole are in full blue.\n}}\n\nHalf of the Irish immigrants to the [[Colonial history of the United States|United States in its colonial era]] (1607\u20131775) came from the Irish province of [[Ulster]] while the other half came from the other three provinces of Ireland ([[Leinster]], [[Munster]], and [[Connacht]]).<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 528\">{{cite book|last=Blessing|first=Patrick J.|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|year=1980|chapter=Irish|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/528 528]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/528}}</ref> In the 17th century, immigration from Ireland to the [[Thirteen Colonies#Population|Thirteen Colonies]] was minimal,<ref name=\"Boyer et. al p. 99\">{{cite book|title=The Enduring Vision: A History of the American People|first1=Paul S.|last1=Boyer|first2=Clifford E.|last2=Clark|first3=Karen|last3=Halttunen|first4=Joseph F.|last4=Kett|first5=Neal|last5=Salisbury|first6=Harvard|last6=Sitkoff|first7=Nancy|last7=Woloch|year=2013|publisher=[[Cengage|Cengage Learning]]|page=99|edition=8th|isbn=978-1133944522}}</ref><ref name=\"Miller et. al 2003 p. 39\">{{cite book|last1=Miller|first1=Kerby A.|author-link1=Kerby A. Miller|last2=Schrier|first2=Arnold|last3=Boling|first3=Bruce D.|last4=Doyle|first4=David N.|title=Irish Immigrants in the Land of Canaan: Letters and Memoirs from Colonial and Revolutionary America, 1675\u20131815|year=2003|place=New York|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=39|isbn=978-0195045130|quote=In the seventeenth century, southern Irish Catholics probably constituted a large majority of the relatively few emigrants from Ireland, perhaps 30,000\u201350,000 in all, who crossed the Atlantic and settled primarily in the West Indies and Chesapeake.}}</ref> confined mostly to male [[Irish indentured servants|indentured servants]] who were primarily [[Irish Catholics|Catholic]],<ref name=\"Miller et. al 2003 p. 39\" /><ref name=\"Swingen p. 21\">{{cite book |first=Abigail L. |last=Swingen |title=Competing Visions of Empire: Labor, Slavery, and the Origins of the British Atlantic Empire |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |location=New Haven, CT |year=2015 |page=21 |isbn=978-0300187540}}</ref> and peaked with 8,000 [[Prisoner of war|prisoner-of-war]] [[Penal transportation|penal transports]] to the [[Chesapeake Colonies]] from the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland]] in the 1650s (out of a total of approximately 10,000 Catholic immigrants from Ireland to the United States prior to the [[American Revolutionary War]] in 1775).<ref name=\"Miller et. al 2003 p. 39\" /><ref name=\"Dunaway 1944 p. 41\">{{cite book|last=Dunaway|first=Wayland F.|title=The Scots-Irish of Colonial Pennsylvania|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company|place=[[Baltimore]]|year=1944|page=41|quote=...there were only 24,000 Catholics in the entire United States in 1783, and this number included many, perhaps a majority, from countries other than Ireland. It appears probable that Ireland furnished no more than 10,000 Catholics in America during the colonial period, and the largest segment of the Catholic population came from England, Germany, and France.}}</ref><ref name=\"Blackburn p. 317\">{{cite book|first=Robin|last=Blackburn|author-link=Robin Blackburn|title=The Making of New World Slavery: From the Baroque to the Modern 1492-1800|place=London|edition=1st|publisher=[[Verso Books]]|year=1997|page=317|isbn=978-1844676316|quote=In the 1650s about eight thousand Irish captives were sent to the American colonies, many of them on ten-year penal contracts.}}</ref><ref name=\"Newman 2015 p. 75\">{{cite book|first=Simon P.|last=Newman|chapter='In Great Slavery and Bondage': White Labor and the Development of Plantation Slavery in British America|editor-last1=Gallup-Diaz|editor-first1=Ignacio|editor-last2=Shankman|editor-first2=Andrew|editor-last3=Silverman|editor-first3=David J.|editor-first4=John M.|editor-last4=Murrin|title=Anglicizing America: Empire, Revolution, Republic|place=[[Philadelphia]]|publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania Press]]|year=2015|page=75|isbn=978-0812246988|quote=One contemporary estimated that some thirty-four thousand men were sent to the Americas, close to one-sixth of Ireland\u2019s adult male population, and more of them went to Barbados than to any other colony.}}</ref> Like the entire indentured servant population in the Chesapeake Colonies at the time, 40 to 50 percent died before completing their contracts (due in large part to the [[Tidewater (region)|Tidewater region's]] highly malignant disease environment), with most not establishing families and dying childless because the population of the Chesapeake Colonies, like the [[Thirteen Colonies]] in the aggregate, was not sex-balanced until the 18th century because three-quarters of the immigrants to the Chesapeake Colonies were male (and in some periods, 4:1 or 6:1 male-to-female) and fewer than 1 percent were over the age of 35. As a consequence, the population only grew due to sustained immigration rather than [[Rate of natural increase|natural increase]], and many of those who survived their indentured servitude contracts left the region.<ref>{{cite book|first=Thomas L.|last=Purvis|editor-first=Richard|editor-last=Balkin|title=Colonial America to 1763|year=1999|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|isbn=978-0816025275|page=[https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/153 153]|url=https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/153}}</ref><ref name=\"Purvis 1999 pp. 162\u2013163\">{{cite book|last1=Purvis|first1=Thomas L.|editor-last=Balkin|editor-first=Richard|title=Colonial America to 1763|year=1999|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|pages=[https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/162 162\u2013163]|isbn=978-0816025275|url=https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/162}}</ref><ref name=\"Fischer pp. 229\u2013231\">{{cite book|last=Fischer|first=David Hackett|author-link=David Hackett Fischer|year=1989|title=Albion's Seed: Four British Folkways in America|title-link=Albion's Seed|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0195069051|pages=229\u2013231}}</ref>\n\n[[Indentured servitude in the Americas|Indentured servitude in North America]] emerged in part due to the high cost of passage across the [[Atlantic Ocean]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Galenson|first=David W.|author-link=David Galenson|journal=[[The Journal of Economic History]]|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|volume=44|issue=1|pages=1\u201326|jstor=2120553|title=The Rise and Fall of Indentured Servitude in the Americas: An Economic Analysis|date=March 1984|doi=10.1017/s002205070003134x}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Whaples|first=Robert|author-link=Robert Whaples|journal=[[The Journal of Economic History]]|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|volume=55|issue=1|pages=140\u2013144|jstor=2123771|title=Where Is There Consensus Among American Economic Historians? The Results of a Survey on Forty Propositions|date=March 1995|doi=10.1017/S0022050700040602|url=http://www.employees.csbsju.edu/jolson/econ315/whaples2123771.pdf}}</ref> and as a consequence, which colonies indentured servants immigrated to depended upon which colonies their patrons chose to immigrate to.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 73\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/73 73]|isbn=978-0385152068}}</ref> While the [[Colony of Virginia]] passed laws prohibiting the free exercise of [[Catholic Church in the Thirteen Colonies|Catholicism during the colonial period]],<ref name=\"Glazier 1999 p. 928\">{{cite book |last=Fogarty |first=Gerald P. |editor-last=Glazier |editor-first=Michael |title=The Encyclopedia of the Irish in America |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse/page/928 |publisher=[[University of Notre Dame Press]] |location=Notre Dame, IN |year=1999 |chapter=Virginia |page=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse/page/928 928]|isbn=978-0268027551}}</ref> the [[Maryland General Assembly|General Assembly]] of the [[Province of Maryland]] enacted laws in 1639 protecting [[freedom of religion]] (following the instructions of a 1632 letter from [[Cecil Calvert, 2nd Baron Baltimore]] to his brother [[Leonard Calvert]], the [[List of colonial governors of Maryland|1st Proprietary-Governor of Maryland]]), and the Maryland General Assembly later passed the 1649 [[Maryland Toleration Act]] explicitly guaranteeing those rights for Catholics.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 pp. 74\u201377\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/74|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|pages=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/74 74\u201377]}}</ref> In 1650, all five major Catholic churches in the [[Thirteen Colonies#New England colonies|eight British American colonies]] were located in Maryland.<ref>{{cite book|first=Thomas L.|last=Purvis|editor-first=Richard|editor-last=Balkin|title=Colonial America to 1763|year=1999|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|isbn=978-0816025275|page=[https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/179 179]|url=https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/179}}</ref> The 17th-century Maryland Catholic community had a high degree of [[social capital]]. Catholic-Protestant [[Interfaith marriage in Christianity|interdenominational marriage]] was not common, Catholic-Protestant intermarriages nearly always resulted in conversion to Catholicism by Protestant marital partners, and children who were born as the result of Catholic-Protestant intermarriages were nearly always raised as Catholics.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 80\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/80 80]}}</ref> Additionally, 17th-century Maryland Catholics often stipulated in their [[Will and testament|wills]] that their children be [[Inheritance|disinherited]] if they renounced [[Catholic Church|Catholicism]].<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 pp. 82\u201383\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/82|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|pages=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/82 82\u201383]}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to 17th-century Maryland, the [[Plymouth Colony|Plymouth]], [[Massachusetts Bay Colony|Massachusetts Bay]] and [[Connecticut Colony|Connecticut Colonies]] restricted suffrage to members of the [[Christian state|established]] [[Puritans|Puritan]] church, while the [[Province of Carolina]] did not restrict suffrage to members of the established [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] church. The [[Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations]] had no established church, while the former [[New Netherland]] colonies ([[Province of New York|New York]], [[Province of New Jersey|New Jersey]], and [[Delaware Colony|Delaware]]) also had no established church under the [[The Duke's Laws|Duke's Laws]], and the [[Frame of Government of Pennsylvania|Frame of Government]] in [[William Penn]]'s 1682 land grant established free exercise of religion for all Christians in the [[Province of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Barck & Lefler pp. 258\u2013259\">{{cite book|last1=Barck|first1=Oscar T.|last2=Lefler|first2=Hugh T.|year=1958|title=Colonial America|place=New York|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|Macmillan]]|pages=258\u2013259}}</ref><ref name=\"Barck & Lefler p. 398\">{{cite book|first1=Oscar T.|last1=Barck|first2=Hugh T.|last2=Lefler|title=Colonial America|publisher=Macmillan|place=New York|year=1958|page=398}}</ref> Following the [[Glorious Revolution]] (1688\u20131689), Catholics were [[Disfranchisement|disenfranchised]] in Maryland, New York, Rhode Island, Carolina, and Virginia,<ref name=\"Barck & Lefler pp. 258\u2013259\" /> although in Maryland, suffrage was restored in 1702.<ref name=\"Purvis 1999 p. 182\">{{cite book|last1=Purvis|first1=Thomas L.|editor-last=Balkin|editor-first=Richard|title=Colonial America to 1763|year=1999|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/182 182]|isbn=978-0816025275|url=https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/182}}</ref> In 1692, the Maryland General Assembly established the [[Church of England]] as the official state church.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 75\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/75 75]}}</ref> In 1698 and 1699, Maryland, Virginia, and Carolina passed laws specifically limiting immigration of Irish Catholic indentured servants.<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 525\u2013527\">{{cite book|last=Blessing|first=Patrick J.|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|year=1980|chapter=Irish|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|pages=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/525 525\u2013527]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/525}}</ref> In 1700, the estimated population of Maryland was 29,600,<ref name=\"Colonial and Pre-Federal Statistics\">{{cite web|title=Colonial and Pre-Federal Statistics|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|page=1168|url=https://www2.census.gov/prod2/statcomp/documents/CT1970p2-13.pdf}}</ref> about 2,500 of which were Catholic.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 79\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/79 79]}}</ref>\n\nIn the 18th century, emigration from Ireland to the Thirteen Colonies shifted from being primarily Catholic to being primarily [[Protestantism in Ireland|Protestant]], and with the exception of the 1790s it would remain so until the mid-to-late 1830s,<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 529\">{{cite book|last=Blessing|first=Patrick J.|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|year=1980|chapter=Irish|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|pages=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/529 529]|isbn=978-0674375123|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/529}}</ref><ref name=\"Purvis 1995 p. 180\">{{cite book|last1=Purvis|first1=Thomas L.|editor-last=Balkin|editor-first=Richard|title=Revolutionary America 1763 to 1800|year=1995|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816025282/page/180 180]|isbn=978-0816025282|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816025282/page/180}}</ref> with [[Presbyterian Church in Ireland|Presbyterians]] constituting the [[Supermajority#Majority of the entire membership|absolute majority]] until 1835.<ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 904\">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Maldwyn A.|year=1980|chapter=Scotch-Irish|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/904 904]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/904}}</ref><ref name=\"Dunaway p. 42\">{{cite book|last=Dunaway|first=Wayland F.|year=1944|title=The Scots-Irish of Colonial Pennsylvania|place=[[Baltimore]]|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company|page=42}}</ref> These Protestant immigrants were principally descended from [[Scottish people|Scottish]] and [[English people|English]] tenant farmer colonists and colonial administrators who had settled the [[Plantations of Ireland]], the largest of which was the [[Plantation of Ulster]],<ref>{{cite book|first=Philip|last=Robinson|title=The Plantation of Ulster: British Settlement in an Irish Landscape, 1600-1670|edition=2nd|publisher=Ulster Historical Foundation|orig-year=1984|year=2000|isbn=978-1903688007|pages=52\u201355}}</ref><ref name=\"Fischer p. 16\">{{cite book|last=Fischer|first=David Hackett|author-link=David Hackett Fischer|year=1989|title=Albion's Seed: Four British Folkways in America|title-link=Albion's Seed|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0195069051|page=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Duffy|first=Sean|title=The Concise History of Ireland|publisher=[[Gill (publisher)|Gill & MacMillan]]|isbn=978-0717138104|page=107|year=2005|quote=...the number of Protestants in Ireland remained small throughout [Queen Elizabeth's] reign, being mostly confined to government officials and new settlers.}}</ref> and these Protestant immigrants primarily migrated as families rather than as individuals.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 129\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/129 129]}}</ref> In Ireland, they are referred to as the \"[[Ulster Scots people|Ulster Scots]]\" and the \"[[Anglo-Irish people|Anglo-Irish]]\" respectively, and because the Protestant population in Ireland was and remains concentrated in Ulster and because Protestants in Northern Ireland on census reports have historically self-identified their [[Demography of Northern Ireland#National identity|national identity]] as \"British\" rather than \"Irish\" or \"Northern Irish,\" Protestants in Ireland are collectively referred to as the \"[[Ulster Protestants]].\"<ref>{{cite article|first=Brian M.|last=Walker|title=We all can be Irish, British or both|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|date=June 10, 2015|access-date=June 13, 2019|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/opinion/news-analysis/we-all-can-be-irish-british-or-both-31290843.html}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, the Ulster Scots and Anglo-Irish intermarried to some degree,<ref name=\"Robinson p. 111\" /> and the Ulster Scots also intermarried with [[Huguenots|Huguenot]] refugees from the [[Kingdom of France]] following the 1685 [[Edict of Fontainebleau]] issued by [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]],<ref name=\"Fischer p. 620\" /><ref name=\"Leyburn p. 128\" /> and some of the Anglo-Irish settlers were actually [[Welsh people|Welsh]] or [[Manx people|Manx]].<ref name=\"Robinson p. 113\" /><ref name=\"Miller et. al 2003 p. 13\" /> However, they seldom intermarried with the [[Irish Catholics|Irish Catholic]] population in part because intermarriage between Protestants and Catholics was banned by the [[Penal Laws#Ascendancy rule 1691\u20131778|Penal Laws]] during the [[Protestant Ascendancy]] (1691\u20131778),{{refn|group=list|name=historic intermarriage|<ref name=\"Robinson p. 111\" /><ref name=\"Fischer p. 620\" /><ref name=\"Leyburn pp. 133\u2013139\">{{cite book|last=Leyburn|first=James G.|year=1962|title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History|url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb|url-access=registration|place=[[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill, NC]]|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|pages=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/133 133\u2013139]}}</ref><ref name=\"Dunaway pp. 9\u201311\">{{cite book|last=Dunaway|first=Wayland F.|year=1944|title=The Scots-Irish of Colonial Pennsylvania|place=[[Baltimore]]|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company.|pages=9\u201311|quote='I have sometimes noticed a little confusion of mind in relation to the phrase 'Scotch-Irish,' as if it meant that the Scotch people had come over and intermarried with the Irish, and thus a combination of two races, two places, two nationalities had taken place. This is by no means the state of the case.'... This does not mean to say, of course... that there was never an instance of marriage between the Ulster Scots and the Irish, for such unions undoubtedly occurred; but all the evidence points to the conclusion that these were rare...}}</ref>}} which rendered any children who were born to extralegal Catholic-Protestant intermarriages [[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]] and legally ineligible to inherit their parents' property under [[Bastard (law of England and Wales)|English law]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Illegitimacy \u2013 law|website=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online|Britannica.com]]|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.]]|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/illegitimacy|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref> In turn, the [[canon law of the Catholic Church]] also [[Marriage in the Catholic Church#Marriage with a non-Catholic Christian|designated Catholic-Protestant intermarriages illegitimate]] until [[Pope Pius VI]] extended [[Pope Benedict XIV]]'s [[Dispensation (canon law)|matrimonial dispensation]] to Ireland in 1785 for the ''[[Tametsi]]'' decree of the [[Council of Trent]] (1563),<ref name=\"CEmixed\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/09698a.htm|title=CATHOLIC ENCYCLOPEDIA: Mixed Marriage|website=www.newadvent.org|access-date=2018-08-18}}</ref> and Irish Catholics almost never converted to Protestant churches during the [[Reformation in Ireland|Reformation]].<ref name=\"Duffy p. 100\u2013107\" /> Catholic-Protestant intermarriage would remain rare in Ireland through the early 20th century.<ref>{{cite article|last1=Fernihough|first1=Alan|last2=O'Grada|first2=Cormac|last3=Walsh|first3=Brendan M.|title=Intermarriage in a Divided Society: Ireland a Century Ago|journal=[[Explorations in Economic History]]|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|year=April 2015|volume=56|pages=1\u201314|url=https://pure.qub.ac.uk/portal/files/13821188/queenswp.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.eeh.2014.11.002}}</ref>\n\nIn 1704, the Maryland General Assembly passed a law which banned the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] from [[Proselytism|proselytizing]], [[Baptism|baptizing]] children other than those with Catholic parents, and [[Evangelism|publicly conducting]] [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Catholic Mass]]. Two months after its passage, the General Assembly modified the legislation to allow Mass to be privately conducted for an 18-month period, and in 1707, the General Assembly passed a law which permanently allowed Mass to be privately conducted. During this period, the General Assembly also began levying taxes on the passage of Irish Catholic indentured servants, and in 1718, the General Assembly required a [[religious test]] for voting that resumed disenfranchisement of Catholics.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 pp. 84\u201385\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/84|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|pages=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/84 84\u201385]}}</ref> However, lax enforcement of [[Penal law (British)|penal laws]] in Maryland (due to its population being overwhelmingly rural) enabled churches on Jesuit-operated farms and plantations to grow and become stable [[Parish in the Catholic Church|parishes]].<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 pp. 87\u201389\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/87|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|pages=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/87 87\u201389]}}</ref> In 1750, of the 30 major Catholic churches in the Thirteen Colonies, 15 were located in Maryland, 11 in Pennsylvania, and 4 in the former New Netherland colonies.<ref>{{cite book|first=Thomas L.|last=Purvis|editor-first=Richard|editor-last=Balkin|title=Colonial America to 1763|year=1999|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|isbn=978-0816025275|page=[https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/181 181]|url=https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/181}}</ref> By 1756, the number of Catholics in Maryland had increased to approximately 7,000,<ref name=\"Taylor 1997\">{{cite book|first=Dale|last=Taylor|title=The Writer's Guide to Everyday Life in Colonial America from 1607-1783|year=1997|page=273|isbn=978-0898799422|quote=In 1756, a Maryland Father Superior estimated 7,000 practicing Catholics in Maryland and 3,000 in Pennsylvania.}}</ref> which increased further to 20,000 by 1765.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 pp. 87\u201389\" /> In Pennsylvania, there were approximately 3,000 Catholics in 1756 and 6,000 by 1765 (although the large majority of the Pennsylvania Catholic population was from [[Catholic Church in Germany|Germany]]).<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 pp. 87\u201389\" /><ref name=\"Taylor 1997\" /><ref name=\"Purvis 1999 p. 183\">{{cite book|last1=Purvis|first1=Thomas L.|editor-last=Balkin|editor-first=Richard|title=Colonial America to 1763|year=1999|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/183 183]|isbn=978-0816025275|url=https://archive.org/details/colonialamericat00purv_0/page/183}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1717 to 1775, though scholarly estimates vary, the most common approximation is that 250,000 immigrants from Ireland emigrated to the Thirteen Colonies.{{refn|group=list|name=numbers|<ref name=\"Fischer p. 606\">{{cite book|first=David Hacket|last=Fischer|author-link=David Hackett Fischer|year=1989|title=Albion's Seed: Four British Folkways in America|title-link=Albion's Seed|place=New York|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0195069051|page=606|quote=more than a quarter-million}}</ref><ref name=\"Rouse p. 32\">{{cite book|first=Parke S.|last=Rouse Jr.|author-link=Parke S. Rouse Jr.|year=1973|title=The Great Wagon Road: From Philadelphia to the South|place=New York|publisher=[[McGraw-Hill Education|McGraw-Hill]]|page=32|quote=200,000}}</ref><ref name=\"Blethen & Wood p. 22\">{{cite book |last1=Blethen |first1=H. Tyler |last2=Wood |first2=Curtis W. |title=From Ulster to Carolina: The Migration of the Scotch-Irish to Southwestern North Carolina |publisher=[[State Archives of North Carolina|North Carolina Division of Archives and History]] |location=Raleigh, NC |year=1998 |isbn=978-0865262799 |page=22 |quote=...250,000 people left for America between 1717 and 1800...20,000 were Anglo-Irish, 20,000 were Gaelic Irish, and the remainder Ulster-Scots...}}</ref><ref name=\"Griffin p. 1\">{{cite book|last=Griffin|first=Patrick|year=2001|title=The People with No Name: Ireland's Ulster Scots, America's Scots Irish, and the Creation of a British Atlantic World, 1689-1764|place=[[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton, NJ]]|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|page=1|quote=more than 100,000}}</ref><ref name=\"Leyburn p. 180\">{{cite book|last=Leyburn|first=James G.|year=1962|title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History|url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb|url-access=registration|place=[[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill, NC]]|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/180 180]|quote=200,000}}</ref><ref name=\"Barck & Lefler p. 285\">{{cite book|last1=Barck|first1=Oscar T.|last2=Lefler|first2=Hugh T.|year=1958|title=Colonial America|place=New York|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|Macmillan]]|page=285|quote=300,000}}</ref><ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 896\">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Maldwyn A.|year=1980|chapter=Scotch-Irish|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/896 896]|isbn=978-0674375123|quote=250,000|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/896}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Blaney|first=Roger|year=1996|title=Presbyterians and the Irish Language|place=[[Belfast]]|publisher=Ulster Historical Foundation|page=4|quote=100,000, and possibly as many as 250,000}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Jim |last=Webb |author-link=Jim Webb |year=2004 |title=Born Fighting: How the Scots-Irish Shaped America |place=New York |publisher=Broadway Books |page=front flap |quote=Between 250,000 to 400,000 Scots-Irish migrated to America in the eighteenth century... |isbn=978-0767916899 |title-link=Born Fighting}}</ref>}} By the end of the [[American Revolutionary War]] in 1783, there were approximately 24,000 to 25,000 Catholics in the United States (including 3,000 [[Slavery in the United States|slaves]]) out of a total population of approximately 3 million (or less than 1 percent).<ref name=\"Colonial and Pre-Federal Statistics\" /><ref name=\"Dunaway 1944 p. 41\" /><ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 86\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/86 86]}}</ref><ref name=\"Purvis 1995 p. 204\">{{cite book|last1=Purvis|first1=Thomas L.|editor-last=Balkin|editor-first=Richard|title=Revolutionary America 1763 to 1800|year=1995|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816025282/page/204 204]|isbn=978-0816025282|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816025282/page/204}}</ref> However, the majority of the Catholic population in the United States during the colonial period came from [[Catholic Church in England and Wales|England]], Germany, and [[Catholic Church in France|France]], not Ireland,<ref name=\"Dunaway 1944 p. 41\" /> despite failed academic efforts by Irish [[Historiography|historiographers]] to demonstrate Irish Catholics as being more numerous in the colonial period than previous scholarship had indicated.<ref name=\"Carroll 2006 p. 28\">{{cite journal|last=Carroll|first=Michael P.|title=How the Irish Became Protestant in America|journal=[[Religion and American Culture]]|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=Winter 2006|volume=16|issue=1|page=28|jstor=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25|doi=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25}}</ref> By 1790, approximately 400,000 people of Irish birth or ancestry lived in the United States (or greater than 10 percent of the total population of approximately 3.9 million),<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 528\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=1790 Fast Facts - History - U.S. Census Bureau|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/through_the_decades/fast_facts/1790_fast_facts.html}}</ref> while the Catholic population grew to approximately 50,000 by 1800 (or less than 1 percent of the total population of approximately 5.3 million) due to increased Catholic emigration from Ireland during the 1790s.<ref name=\"Purvis 1995 p. 180\" /><ref name=\"Purvis 1995 p. 204\" /><ref name=\"Purvis 1995 p. 197\">{{cite book|last1=Purvis|first1=Thomas L.|editor-last=Balkin|editor-first=Richard|title=Revolutionary America 1763 to 1800|year=1995|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816025282/page/197 197]|isbn=978-0816025282|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816025282/page/197}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1800 Fast Facts - History - U.S. Census Bureau|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/through_the_decades/fast_facts/1800_fast_facts.html}}</ref>\n\nIn the 18th-century Thirteen Colonies and the independent United States, while [[interethnic marriage]] among Catholics remained a dominant pattern, Catholic-Protestant intermarriage became more common (notably in the [[Shenandoah Valley]] where intermarriage among Ulster Protestants and the small number of Irish Catholics in particular was not uncommon or stigmatized),<ref name=\"Miller pp. 80\u201381\">{{cite book|first=Kerby A.|last=Miller|author-link=Kerby A. Miller|editor-first=Charles|editor-last=Fanning|chapter='Scotch-Irish' Myths and 'Irish' Identities|title=New Perspectives on the Irish Diaspora|publisher=[[Southern Illinois University Press]]|edition=1st|year=2000|pages=80\u201381|isbn=978-0809323449}}</ref> and while fewer Catholic parents required that their children be disinherited in their wills if they renounced Catholicism, it remained more common among Catholic parents to do so if their children renounced their parents faith in proportion to the rest of the U.S. population.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 86\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/86 86]}}</ref> Despite this, many Irish Catholics that immigrated to the United States from 1770 to 1830 converted to [[Baptists in the United States|Baptist]] and [[History of Methodism in the United States|Methodist]] churches during the [[Second Great Awakening]] (1790\u20131840).<ref name=\"Carroll 2006 p. 32\">{{cite journal|last=Carroll|first=Michael P.|title=How the Irish Became Protestant in America|journal=[[Religion and American Culture]]|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=Winter 2006|volume=16|issue=1|page=32|jstor=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25|doi=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25}}</ref><ref name=\"Carroll 2006 p. 38\">{{cite journal|last=Carroll|first=Michael P.|title=How the Irish Became Protestant in America|journal=[[Religion and American Culture]]|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=Winter 2006|volume=16|issue=1|page=38|jstor=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25|doi=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25}}</ref> In between the end of the American Revolutionary War in 1783 and the [[War of 1812]], 100,000 immigrants came from Ulster to the United States.<ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 903\">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Maldwyn A.|year=1980|chapter=Scotch-Irish|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/904 904]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/904}}</ref> During the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] (1792\u20131802) and [[Napoleonic Wars]] (1803\u20131815), there was a 22-year [[economic expansion]] in Ireland due to increased need for agricultural products for British soldiers and an expanding population in England. Following the conclusion of the [[Hundred Days|War of the Seventh Coalition]] and [[Napoleon]]'s exile to [[Saint Helena]] in 1815, there was a [[Post-Napoleonic depression|six-year]] international [[Depression (economics)|economic depression]] that led to plummeting agricultural prices in Ireland.<ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 904\" /><ref name=\"Blessing 1980 pp. 528\u2013529\">{{cite book|last=Blessing|first=Patrick J.|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|year=1980|chapter=Irish|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|pages=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/528 528\u2013529]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/528}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1815 to 1845, 500,000 more immigrants came from Ulster to the United States,<ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 904\" /><ref name=\"Faragher p. 385\">{{cite book|last=Faragher|first=John Mack|title=The Encyclopedia of Colonial and Revolutionary America|publisher=[[Da Capo Press]]|year=1996|isbn=978-0306806872|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofco00fara/|page=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofco00fara/page/385 385]}}</ref> as part of a migration of approximately 1 million immigrants from Ireland from 1820 to 1845.<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 pp. 528\u2013529\" /> In 1820, following the [[Louisiana Purchase]] in 1804 and the [[Adams\u2013On\u00eds Treaty]] in 1819, the Catholic population of the United States had grown to 195,000 (or approximately 2 percent of the total population of approximately 9.6 million).<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 pp. 160\u2013161\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/160|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|pages=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/160 160\u2013161]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1820 Fast Facts - History - U.S. Census Bureau|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/through_the_decades/fast_facts/1820_fast_facts.html}}</ref> By 1840, along with resumed immigration from Germany by the 1820s,<ref name=\"Conzen 1980 p. 409\">{{cite book|last=Conzen|first=Kathleen Neils|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|year=1980|chapter=Germans|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/409 409]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/409}}</ref> the Catholic population grew to 663,000 (or approximately 4 percent out of the total population of 17.1 million).<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 pp. 55\u201356\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The Irish Americans: A History|pages=55\u201356|year=2008|isbn=978-1596914193|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]|quote=By 1840 the Catholic population had increased to 663,000. The increase was due mainly to the large numbers of immigrants from Ireland and Germany.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1840 Fast Facts - History - U.S. Census Bureau|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/through_the_decades/fast_facts/1840_fast_facts.html}}</ref> Following the [[Phytophthora infestans|potato blight]] in late 1845 that initiated the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]] in Ireland, from 1846 to 1851, more than 1 million more Irish immigrated to the United States, 90 percent of whom were Catholic.<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 529\" /><ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 905\">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Maldwyn A.|year=1980|chapter=Scotch-Irish|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/905 905]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/905}}</ref> Many of the Famine immigrants to [[New York City]] required [[quarantine]] on [[Staten Island]] or [[Roosevelt Island|Blackwell's Island]] and thousands died from [[typhoid fever]] or [[cholera]] for reasons directly or indirectly related to the Famine.<ref name=\"Glazier 1999 p. 681\">{{cite book|last=Ridge|first=John|editor-last=Glazier|editor-first=Michael|title=The Encyclopedia of the Irish in America|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse/page/681|publisher=[[University of Notre Dame Press]]|location=Notre Dame, IN|year=1999|chapter=New York City|page=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse/page/681 681]|isbn=978-0268027551}}</ref> By 1850, following the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] (1846\u20131848) that left a residual population of 80,000 [[Mexican Americans|Mexicans]] in the [[Southwestern United States]],<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 134\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=978-0385152068|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/134 134]}}</ref> and along with increasing immigration from Germany,<ref name=\"Conzen 1980 p. 410\">{{cite book|last=Conzen|first=Kathleen Neils|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|year=1980|chapter=Germans|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/410 410]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/410}}</ref> the Catholic population in the United States had grown to 1.6 million (or approximately 7 percent of the total population of approximately 23.2 million).<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 pp. 160\u2013161\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=1850 Fast Facts - History - U.S. Census Bureau|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/through_the_decades/fast_facts/1850_fast_facts.html}}</ref> Despite the small increase in Catholic-Protestant intermarriage following the American Revolutionary War,<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 86\" /> Catholic-Protestant intermarriage remained uncommon in the United States in the 19th century.<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 228\" />\n\nHistorians have characterized the etymology of the term \"[[Scotch-Irish Americans|Scotch-Irish]]\" as obscure,<ref name=\"Leyburn p. 328\u2013329\">{{cite book|last=Leyburn|first=James G.|title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History|url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb|url-access=registration|pages=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/328 328\u2013329]|orig-year=1962|year=1989|edition=Reprint|isbn=978-0807842591|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]}}</ref> and the term itself is misleading and confusing to the extent that even its usage by authors in historic works of literature about the Scotch-Irish (such as ''The Mind of the South'' by [[W. J. Cash]]) is often incorrect.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Barck|first1=Oscar T.|last2=Lefler|first2=Hugh T.|title=Colonial America|place=New York|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|Macmillan]]|page=285|year=1958}}</ref><ref name=\"Dunaway pp. 9\u201311\"/><ref name=\"Carroll 2006 p. 46\">{{cite journal|last=Carroll|first=Michael P.|title=How the Irish Became Protestant in America|journal=[[Religion and American Culture]]|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=Winter 2006|volume=16|issue=1|page=46|jstor=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25|doi=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25}}</ref> Historians [[David Hackett Fischer]] and James G. Leyburn note that usage of the term is unique to [[North American English]] and it is rarely used by British historians, or in Scotland or Ireland.<ref name=\"Fischer p. 618\">{{cite book|last=Fischer|first=David Hackett|author-link=David Hackett Fischer|year=1989|title=Albion's Seed: Four British Folkways in America|title-link=Albion's Seed|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0195069051|page=618}}</ref><ref name=\"Leyburn p. xi\">{{cite book|last=Leyburn|first=James G.|title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History|url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb|url-access=registration|page=xi|orig-year=1962|year=1989|edition=Reprint|isbn=978-0807842591|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]}}</ref> The first recorded usage of the term was by [[Elizabeth I of England]] in 1573 in reference to [[Scottish Gaelic|Gaelic-speaking]] [[Gaels|Scottish Highlanders]] who crossed the [[Irish Sea]] and intermarried with the [[Irish Catholics|Irish Catholic]] natives of Ireland.<ref name=\"Leyburn p. 328\u2013329\" /> While Protestant immigrants from Ireland in 18th century were more commonly identified as \"Anglo-Irish,\" and while some preferred to self-identify as \"Anglo-Irish,\"<ref name=\"Fischer p. 618\" /> usage of \"Scotch-Irish\" in reference to [[Ulster Scots people|Ulster Scots]] who immigrated to the United States in the 18th century likely became common among [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalians]] and [[Quakers]] in Pennsylvania, and records show that usage of the term with this meaning was made as early as 1757 by the Anglo-Irish philosopher [[Edmund Burke]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunaway|first=Wayland F.|year=1944|title=The Scots-Irish of Colonial Pennsylvania|place=[[Baltimore]]|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company|page=8|quote=...it is evident that the Scotch-Irish were being very generally so called soon after they had begun to arrive in Pennsylvania in large numbers, and it is probable that the name was first applied to them by the Episcopalians and Quakers, who by no means intended it to be complimentary.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Burke|first=Edmund|author-link=Edmund Burke|title=An Account Of The European Settlements In America|volume=2|page=285|publisher=J. H. Wilkins & Company and Hilliard, Gray, & Co.|orig-year=1757|year=1835|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wp8-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PR1&dq=An+Account+of+the+European+Settlements+in+America+1835#v=onepage&q&f=false|quote=They are chiefly Presbyterians from the northern part of Ireland, who in America are generally called Scotch-Irish.}}</ref>\n\nHowever, multiple historians have noted that from the time of the [[American Revolutionary War]] until 1850, the term largely fell out of usage, because most Ulster Protestants self-identified as \"Irish\" until large waves of immigration by Irish Catholics both during and after the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|1840s Great Famine]] in Ireland led those Ulster Protestants in America who lived in proximity to the new immigrants to change their self-identification from \"Irish\" to \"Scotch-Irish,\"{{refn|group=list|name=linguistic-usage|<ref name=\"Miller pp. 80\u201381\" /><ref name=\"Leyburn p. 331\">{{cite book|last=Leyburn|first=James G.|title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History|url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/331 331]|orig-year=1962|year=1989|edition=Reprint|isbn=978-0807842591|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. x\" />}} while those Ulster Protestants who did not live in proximity to Irish Catholics continued to self-identify as \"Irish,\" or as time went on, to start self-identifying as being of \"[[American ancestry]].\"<ref name=\"Webb p. 15\" /><ref name=\"Barkan2013\" /> While those historians note that renewed usage of \"Scotch-Irish\" after 1850 was motivated by [[Anti-Irish sentiment|anti-Irish]] and [[Anti-Catholicism in the United States|anti-Catholic prejudices]] among Ulster Protestants,<ref name=\"Leyburn p. 331\" /><ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. x\" /> considering the historically low rates of intermarriage between Protestants and Catholics in both Ireland and the United States,{{refn|group=list|name=US&IrelandIntermarriage|<ref name=\"Robinson p. 111\" /><ref name=\"Fischer p. 620\" /><ref name=\"Leyburn pp. 133\u2013139\" /><ref name=\"Dunaway pp. 9\u201311\" /><ref name=\"Fernihough, O'Grada & Walsh 2015\" /><ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 228\" />}} as well as the relative frequency of [[Interethnic marriage|interethnic]] and [[Interfaith marriage in Christianity|interdenominational marriage]] amongst Protestants in Ulster,{{refn|group=list|name=IrelandProtestantinterethnic&interdenominationalmarriage|<ref name=\"Robinson p. 111\" /><ref name=\"Robinson p. 113\" /><ref name=\"Leyburn p. 128\" /><ref name=\"Fischer p. 620\" />}} and the fact that not all Protestant migrants from Ireland historically were Ulster Scots,<ref name=\"Blethen & Wood p. 22\" /> James G. Leyburn argued for retaining its usage for reasons of utility and preciseness,<ref name=\"Leyburn p. 333\">{{cite book|last=Leyburn|first=James G.|title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History|url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/333 333]|orig-year=1962|year=1989|edition=Reprint|isbn=978-0807842591|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]}}</ref> while historian Wayland F. Dunaway also argued for retention for historical precedent and [[linguistic description]].<ref name=\"Dunaway p. 7\">{{cite book|last=Dunaway|first=Wayland F.|year=1944|title=The Scots-Irish of Colonial Pennsylvania|place=[[Baltimore]]|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company|page=7}}</ref>\n\nDuring the colonial period, Scots-Irish settled in the [[southern Appalachia]]n backcountry and in the [[The Carolinas|Carolina]] [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Parke|last=Rouse, Jr.|title=The Great Wagon Road: From Philadelphia to the South|publisher=Dietz Press|year=1992|edition=1st|isbn=978-0875170657}}</ref> They became the primary cultural group in these areas, and their descendants were in the vanguard of westward movement through [[Virginia]] into [[Tennessee]] and [[Kentucky]], and thence into [[Arkansas]], [[Missouri]] and [[Texas]]. By the 19th century, through intermarriage with settlers of English and German ancestry, the descendants of the Scots-Irish lost their identification with Ireland. \"This generation of pioneers...was a generation of Americans, not of Englishmen or Germans or Scots-Irish.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Leyburn|first=James G.|title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History|url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb|url-access=registration|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|edition=Reprint|year=1989|orig-year=1962|pages=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/317 317\u2013319]|isbn=978-0807842591}}</ref> The two groups had little initial interaction in America, as the 18th-century Ulster immigrants were predominantly [[Protestant]] and had become settled largely in upland regions of the American interior, while the huge wave of 19th-century Catholic immigrant families settled primarily in the Northeast and Midwest port cities such as [[Boston]], [[Philadelphia]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], or [[Chicago]]. However, beginning in the early 19th century, many Irish migrated individually to the interior for work on large-scale infrastructure projects such as [[Erie Canal#Impact|canals]] and, later in the century, [[First Transcontinental Railroad|railroads]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Collins|first=Ryan M.|title=Irish Gandy Dancer: A Tale of Building the Transcontinental Railroad|year=2011|publisher=[[CreateSpace]]|location=[[Seattle]]|isbn=978-1452826318|page=198}}</ref>\n\nThe Scots-Irish settled mainly in the colonial \"back country\" of the [[Appalachia|Appalachian Mountain]] region, and became the prominent ethnic strain in the culture that developed there.<ref>{{cite book|last=Leyburn|first=James G.|title=The Scotch-Irish: A Social History|url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb|url-access=registration|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|edition=Reprint|year=1989|orig-year=1962|pages=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/184 184\u2013255]|isbn=978-0807842591}}</ref> The descendants of Scots-Irish settlers had a great influence on the later culture of the [[Southern United States]] in particular and the culture of the United States in general through such contributions as [[American folk music]], [[country music|country and western]] music, and [[stock car racing]], which became popular throughout the country in the late 20th century.<ref>{{cite book|first=Jim|last=Webb|author-link=Jim Webb|title=Born Fighting: How the Scots-Irish Shaped America|publisher=[[Broadway Books]]|year=2004|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bornfightinghows00webb/page/253 253\u2013264]|isbn=978-0767916899|title-link=Born Fighting}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Charlescarrollofcarrollton.jpg|thumb|right|[[Charles Carroll of Carrollton|Charles Carroll]], the sole [[Irish Catholics|Catholic]] signer of the [[United States Declaration of Independence|U.S. Declaration of Independence]], was the descendant of Irish nobility in [[County Tipperary]]. Signers [[Matthew Thornton]], [[George Taylor (Pennsylvania politician)|George Taylor]] and [[James Smith (Pennsylvania politician)|James Smith]] were all born in Ireland but were [[Ulster Protestants|Protestants]].]]\n\nIrish immigrants of this period participated in significant numbers in the [[American Revolution]], leading one British major general to testify at the [[House of Commons of Great Britain|House of Commons]] that \"half the rebel [[Continental Army]] were from Ireland.\"<ref>{{cite book|first=Philip H.|last=Bagenal|title=The American Irish and their Influence on Irish Politics|publisher=[[BiblioBazaar]]|year=2009|orig-year=1882|pages=12\u201313|isbn=978-1103404650}}</ref> Irish Americans signed the foundational documents of the United States\u2014the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]] and the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]]\u2014and, beginning with [[Andrew Jackson]], served as President.\n\n====Irish Catholics in the South====\nIn 1820 Irish-born [[John England (bishop)|John England]] became the first Catholic bishop in the mainly Protestant city of [[Charleston, South Carolina]]. During the 1820s and '30s, Bishop England defended the Catholic minority against Protestant prejudices. In 1831 and 1835, he established free schools for free [[African American]] children. Inflamed by the propaganda of the [[American Anti-Slavery Society]], a mob raided the Charleston post office in 1835 and the next day turned its attention to England's school. England led Charleston's \"Irish Volunteers\" to defend the school. Soon after this, however, all schools for \"free blacks\" were closed in Charleston, and England acquiesced.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Joseph|last=Kelly|title=Charleston's Bishop John England and American Slavery|journal=New Hibernia Review|publisher=[[University of St. Thomas (Minnesota)|University of St. Thomas]]|year=2001|volume=5|issue=4|pages=48\u201356|jstor=20557774|doi= 10.1353/nhr.2001.0063}}</ref>\n\nThe Irish Catholics concentrated in a few medium-sized cities, where they were highly visible, especially in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]] and [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"Watkin\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Niehaus|first=Earl F.|title=The Irish in New Orleans, 1800\u20131860|year=1976|orig-year=1965|publisher=Arno Press|edition=2nd|isbn=978-0405093524}}</ref>  They often became precinct leaders in the [[History of the United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party Organizations]], strongly opposed [[abolition of slavery]], and generally favored preserving the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] in 1860, when they voted for [[Stephen A. Douglas|Stephen Douglas]].<ref>{{cite book|first=David T.|last=Gleeson|title=The Green and the Gray: The Irish in the Confederate States of America|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LcU7AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30|year=2013|isbn=978-1469627243|edition=Reprint|pages=30\u201334}}</ref>\n\nAfter secession in 1861, the Irish Catholic community supported the Confederacy  and 20,000 served in the Confederate Army.  Gleason says:\n\n{{quote|Support for Irish Confederate soldiers from home was vital both for encouraging them to stay in the army and to highlight to native white southerners that the entire Irish community was behind the Confederacy. Civilian leaders of the Irish and the South did embrace the Confederate national project and most became advocates of a 'hard-war' policy.<ref>{{cite book|first=David T.|last=Gleeson|title=The Green and the Gray: The Irish in the Confederate States of America|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LcU7AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30|year=2013|isbn=978-1469627243|edition=Reprint|pages=41, 59, & 112}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Devitt|first=Jerome|title=Devitt on Gleeson, 'The Green and the Gray: The Irish in the Confederate States of America'|url=https://networks.h-net.org/node/12840/reviews/65781/devitt-gleeson-green-and-gray-irish-confederate-states-america|year=2015|publisher=[[H-Net]]}}</ref>}}\n\nIrish nationalist [[John Mitchel]] lived in Tennessee and Virginia during his exile from Ireland and was one of the South's most outspoken supporters during the American Civil War through his newspapers the ''Southern Citizen'' and the ''Richmond Enquirer''.<ref>{{cite book|first=Bryan P.|last=McGovern|title=John Mitchel: Irish Nationalist, Southern Secessionist|publisher=[[University of Tennessee Press]]|year=2009|isbn=978-1572336544}}</ref>\n\nAlthough most began as unskilled laborers, Irish Catholics in the South achieved average or above average economic status by 1900. David T. Gleeson emphasizes how well they were accepted by society:\n\n{{quote|Native tolerance, however, was also a very important factor in Irish integration [into Southern society].... Upper-class southerners, therefore, did not object to the Irish, because Irish immigration never threatened to overwhelm their cities or states.... The Irish were willing to take on potentially high-mortality occupations, thereby sparing valuable slave property. Some employers objected not only to the cost of Irish labor but also to the rowdiness of their foreign-born employees. Nevertheless, they recognized the importance of the Irish worker to the protection of slavery.... The Catholicism practiced by Irish immigrants was of little concern to Southern natives.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gleeson|first=David T.|title=The Irish in the South, 1815\u20131877|pages=192\u201393|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|year=2001|isbn=978-0807849682}}</ref>}}\n\n===Mid-19th century and later===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; margin:1em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |Irish immigration to the United States (1820\u20131975)<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 528\" />\n|-\n| Period|| Number of<br />immigrants || Period || Number of<br />immigrants\n|-\n| 1820\u20131830 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 54,338 || 1911\u20131920 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 146,181\n|-\n| 1831\u20131840 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 207,381 || 1921\u20131930 ||align=\"right\"| 220,591\n|-\n| 1841\u20131850|| style=\"text-align:right;\"|780,719 || 1931\u20131940 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|13,167\n|-\n| 1851\u20131860|| style=\"text-align:right;\"|914,119 || 1941\u20131950|| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 26,967\n|-\n| 1861\u20131870|| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 435,778 || 1951\u20131960|| style=\"text-align:right;\"|57,332\n|-\n| 1871\u20131880 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 436,871 || 1961\u20131970 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|37,461\n|-\n| 1881\u20131890 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 655,482 || 1971\u20131975 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,559\n|-\n| 1891\u20131900 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 388,416 || || style=\"text-align:right;\"|\n|-\n| 1901\u20131910  || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 399,065 || || style=\"text-align:right;\"| \n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |Total : 4,720,427\n|}\n\nBetween 1851 and 1920, 3.3 to 3.7 million Irish immigrated to the United States,<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 128\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/128 128]|isbn=978-0385152068}}</ref><ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 528\" /> including more than 90 percent of the more than 1 million Ulster Protestant emigrants out of Ireland from 1851 to 1900.<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. 78\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The Irish Americans: A History|page=78|year=2008|isbn=978-1596914193|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 905\" /> Following the Great Famine, emigration from Ireland came primarily from [[Munster]] and [[Connacht]],<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. 78\" /> while 28 percent of all immigrants from Ireland from 1851 to 1900 continued to come from Ulster. Ulster immigration continued to account for as much as 20 percent of all immigration from Ireland to the United States in the 1880s and 1890s,<ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 905\" /> and still accounted for 19 percent of all immigration from Ireland to the United States from 1900 to 1909 and 25 percent from 1910 to 1914.<ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 907\">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Maldwyn A.|year=1980|chapter=Scotch-Irish|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/907 907]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/904}}</ref> The Catholic population in the United States grew to 3.1 million by 1860 (or approximately 10 percent of the total U.S. population of 31.4 million),<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 pp. 110\u2013111\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The Irish Americans: A History|pages=110\u2013111|year=2008|isbn=978-1596914193|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1860 Fast Facts - History - U.S. Census Bureau|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/through_the_decades/fast_facts/1860_fast_facts.html}}</ref> to 6.3 million by 1880 (or approximately 13 percent of the total U.S. population of 50.2 million),<ref name=\"Shifflett 1996 p. 84\">{{cite book|last=Shifflett|first=Crandall|title=Victorian America: 1876 to 1913|page=84|year=1996|isbn=978-0816025312|place=New York|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1880 Fast Facts - History - U.S. Census Bureau|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/through_the_decades/fast_facts/1880_fast_facts.html}}</ref> and further to 19.8 million by 1920 (or approximately 19 percent of the total U.S. population of 106 million).<ref name=\"Shifflett 1996 p. 84\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=1920 Fast Facts - History - U.S. Census Bureau|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/through_the_decades/fast_facts/1920_fast_facts.html}}</ref>\n\nHowever, due to continued immigration from Germany,<ref name=\"Conzen 1980 p. 410\" /> and beginning in the 1880s, waves of immigration from [[Italian Americans|Italy]], [[Polish Americans|Poland]], and [[Canada]] (by [[French Canadian Americans|French Canadians]]) as well as from Mexico from 1900 to 1920,<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 pp. 130\u2013134\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The American Catholic Experience: A History from Colonial Times to the Present|url=https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola|url-access=registration|year=1985|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/americancatholic00dola/page/130 130\u2013134]|isbn=978-0385152068}}</ref> Irish Catholics never accounted for a majority of the Catholic population in the United States through 1920.<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. 108\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The Irish Americans: A History|page=108|year=2008|isbn=978-1596914193|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. 231\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The Irish Americans: A History|page=231|year=2008|isbn=978-1596914193|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]}}</ref> In the 1920s, an additional 220,000 immigrants from Ireland came to the United States,<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 528\" />  with emigration from Ulster falling off to 10,000 of 126,000 immigrants from Ireland (or less than 10 percent) between 1925 and 1930.<ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 907\" /> Following the [[Immigration Act of 1924]] and the [[Great Depression]],<ref>{{cite book |first=Robert K. |last=Murray |title=The 103rd Ballot: Democrats and the Disaster in Madison Square Garden |location=New York |publisher=Harper & Row |year=1976 |page=[https://archive.org/details/103rdballotdemoc0000murr/page/7 7] |isbn=978-0-06-013124-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/103rdballotdemoc0000murr/page/7 }}</ref><ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 540\">{{cite book|last=Blessing|first=Patrick J.|editor-last=Thernstrom|editor-first=Stephan|editor-link=Stephan Thernstrom|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|year=1980|chapter=Irish|place=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]]|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/540 540]|isbn=978-0674375123|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardencyclope00ther/page/540}}</ref> from 1930 to 1975, only 141,000 more immigrants came from Ireland to the United States.<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 528\" /> Improving economic conditions during the [[Post\u2013World War II economic expansion]] and the passage of the restrictive [[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965]] contributed to the decline in mass immigration from Ireland.<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 540\" /> Due to the [[early 1980s recession]], 360,000 Irish emigrated out of the country, with the majority going to England and many to the United States (including approximately 40,000 to 150,000 on overstayed [[travel visa]]s as [[Illegal immigration to the United States|undocumented aliens]]).<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. 282\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The Irish Americans: A History|page=282|year=2008|isbn=978-1596914193|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in the 1970s, surveys of self-identified Irish Americans found that consistent majorities of Irish Americans also self-identified as being Protestant.<ref name=\"Carroll 2006 p. 25\" /><ref name=\"RNS 3-17-2014\" /> While there was a greater total number of immigrants after immigration from Ireland transitioned to being primarily Catholic in the mid-to-late 1830s,<ref name=\"Blessing 1980 p. 529\" /><ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 129\" /><ref name=\"Jones 1980 p. 904\" /><ref name=\"Dunaway p. 42\" /> [[Total fertility rate|fertility rates]] in the United States were lower from 1840 to 1970 after immigration from Ireland became primarily Catholic than they were from 1700 to 1840 when immigration was primarily Protestant.<ref>{{cite article|last=Wells|first=Robert V.|title=Family Size and Fertility Control in Eighteenth-Century America: A Study of Quaker Families|year=1971|journal=[[Population Studies (journal)|Population Studies]]|volume=25|issue=1|pages=73\u201382|publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]]|jstor=2172749}}</ref><ref>{{cite article|last=Haines|first=Michael R.|title=The Population of the United States, 1790\u20131920|year=1994|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]]|url=https://www.nber.org/papers/h0056.pdf|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite article|last1=Bailey|first1=Martha|last2=Hershbein|first2=Brad J.|title=U.S. Fertility Rates and Childbearing, 1800 to 2010|year=2015|publisher=[[University of Michigan]]|url=http://www-personal.umich.edu/~baileymj/OUP_fertility_9_30_15.pdf|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Also, while Irish immigrants to the United States in the early 20th century had higher fertility rates than the U.S. population as a whole, they had lower fertility rates than German immigrants to the United States during the same time period and lower fertility rates than the contemporaneous population of Ireland, and subsequent generations had lower fertility rates than the emigrant generation.<ref>{{cite article|last1=Guinnane|first1=Timothy W.|last2=Moehling|first2=Carolyn M.|last3=\u00d3 Gr\u00e1da|first3=Cormac|title=The Fertility of the Irish in America in 1910|publisher=[[Yale University]]|year=2002|url=http://www.econ.yale.edu/growth_pdf/cdp848.pdf|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> This is due to the fact that despite coming from the rural regions of an agrarian society, Irish immigrants in the post-Famine migration generally immigrated to the [[List of United States urban areas|urban areas of the United States]] because by 1850 the costs of moving to a [[Rural areas in the United States|rural area]] and establishing a farm was beyond the financial means of most Irish immigrants.<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 p. 85\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The Irish Americans: A History|page=85|year=2008|isbn=978-1596914193|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]}}</ref>\n\nDespite Catholic-Protestant intermarriage becoming more common in the 20th century than the 19th century,<ref name=\"Dolan 1985 p. 228\" /> and [[interfaith marriage]] in the United States becoming more common beginning in the 1960s, changes in interdenominational marriage among Christians has remained largely flat during the same time period and the Catholic population has had the highest secularization rate of any Christian denomination in the United States.<ref>{{cite article|last=Murphy|first=Caryle|title=Interfaith marriage is common in U.S., particularly among the recently wed|date=June 2, 2015|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/06/02/interfaith-marriage/|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite article|title=Chapter 2: Religious Switching and Intermarriage|date=May 12, 2015|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|url=https://www.pewforum.org/2015/05/12/chapter-2-religious-switching-and-intermarriage/|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> In the 1990s, the [[Celtic Tiger|Irish economy began to boom]] again, and by the turn of the 21st century, immigration to Ireland from the United States began to consistently exceed immigration from Ireland to the United States.<ref name=\"Dolan 2008 pp. 283\u2013284\">{{cite book|last=Dolan|first=Jay P.|title=The Irish Americans: A History|pages=283\u2013284|year=2008|isbn=978-1596914193|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]}}</ref>\n\nIrish immigration had greatly increased beginning in the 1830s due to the need for unskilled labor in canal building, lumbering, and construction works in the [[Northeast United States|Northeast]].<ref name=\"ruckenstein195\">Ruckenstein and O'Malley (2003), p. 195.</ref> The large [[Erie Canal]] project was one such example where Irishmen were many of the laborers. Small but tight communities developed in growing cities such as Philadelphia, Boston, and New York.\n\n[[File:Irish Memorial in Philadelphia 1.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.25|\"Leacht Cuimhneach\u00e1in na nGael\", [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Irish famine]] memorial located on Penn's Landing, [[Philadelphia]]]]\nFrom 1820 to 1860, 1,956,557 Irish arrived, 75% of these after the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Irish Famine]] (or ''The Great Hunger'', {{lang-ga|An Gorta M\u00f3r}}) of 1845\u20131852, struck.<ref name=\"libraryofcongress\">{{cite web| url = http://memory.loc.gov/learn/features/immig/irish2.html | title = Irish-Catholic Immigration to America | publisher = Library of Congress | accessdate = 2008-04-13}}</ref> According to a 2019 study, \"the sons of farmers and illiterate men were more likely to emigrate than their literate and skilled counterparts. Emigration rates were highest in poorer farming communities with stronger migrant networks.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Connor|first=Dylan Shane|date=2019|title=The Cream of the Crop? Geography, Networks, and Irish Migrant Selection in the Age of Mass Migration|journal=The Journal of Economic History|language=en|volume=79|issue=1|pages=139\u2013175|doi=10.1017/S0022050718000682|issn=0022-0507|url=http://www.escholarship.org/uc/item/3n5876cb}}</ref>\n\nOf the total [[Irish diaspora|Irish immigrants]] to the U.S. from 1820 to 1860, many died crossing the ocean due to disease and dismal conditions of what became known as [[coffin ship]]s.<ref name=\"ruckenstein195\" />\n\nMost Irish immigrants to the United States during this period favored large cities because they could create their own communities for support and protection in a new environment.<ref>{{cite book| last=Diner| first=Hasia R.| title=Erin's Daughters| pages=40\u201341}}</ref>   Cities with large numbers of Irish immigrants included Boston, Philadelphia, and New York, as well as [[Pittsburgh]], [[Baltimore]], [[Detroit]], [[Chicago]], [[Cleveland]], [[St. Louis]], [[History of the Irish in Saint Paul|St. Paul]], [[San Francisco]], and [[Los Angeles]].\n\n[[File:Thomas A. Butler (retouched).jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Thomas Ambrose Butler]], an Irish Catholic priest, was a leading voice in urging Irish immigrants to colonize Kansas]]\n[[File:TollgateRoscommon.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Gravestone]] in [[Forest Hills (Boston)|Boston]] [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] [[cemetery]] erected in memory of [[County Roscommon]] native born shortly before the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]]]]\nWhile many Irish did stay near large cities, countless others were part of westward expansion. They were enticed by tales of gold, and by the increasing opportunities for work and land. In 1854, the government opened Kansas Territory to settlers.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=From the Bottom Up: the story of Irish in Kansas City|last=O'Neil|first=Pat|publisher=Seat O' the Pants Publishing|year=2000|isbn=|location=Kansas City|pages=4, 8, 16, 36}}</ref> While many people in general moved to take advantage of the unsettled land, Irish were an important part. Many Irish men were physical laborers. In order to civilize{{clarify|date=November 2018}} the west, many strong men were needed to build the towns and cities. [[Kansas City metropolitan area|Kansas City]] was one city that was built by Irish immigrants.<ref name=\":0\" />  Much of its population today is of Irish descent.  Another reason for Irish migration west was the expansion of railroads. Railway work was a common occupation among immigrant men because workers were in such high demand. Many Irish men followed the expansion of railroads, and ended up settling in places that they built in.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Missouri Irish: the original history of the Irish in Missouri|last=O'Laughlin|first=Michael|publisher=Irish Genealogical Foundation|year=2007|isbn=|location=Kansas City|pages=36}}</ref> Since the Irish were a large part of those Americans moving west, much of their culture can still be found today.\n\n====Civil War through the early 20th century====\n{{Main|Irish Americans in the American Civil War}}\n[[File:Irish American2.png|thumb|Concentration of people born in Ireland in 1870 Census]]\n\nDuring the [[American Civil War]], Irish Americans volunteered for the [[Union Army]] in high numbers, and at least 38 Union regiments had the word \"Irish\" in their titles. 144,221 Union soldiers were born in Ireland; additionally, perhaps an equal number of Union soldiers were of Irish descent.<ref>Gillespie, W.T. (2001). [http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA406629 \"The United States Civil War Causal Agent for Irish Assimilation and Acceptance in US Society\"]</ref> Many immigrant soldiers formed their own regiments, such as the [[Irish Brigade (U.S.)|Irish Brigade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/topics/ethnic/irish/index.html|title=The Irish and the U.S. Army|website=History.army.mil|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Christian G. Samito 2009\">Christian G. Samito, ''Becoming American under fire: Irish Americans, African Americans, and the politics of citizenship during the Civil War era'' (2009)</ref><ref name=\"Susanna J. Ural 2006\">Susanna J. Ural, ''The heart and the Eagle: Irish-American volunteers and the Union army, 1861\u20131865'' (2006)</ref>\n\nGeneral [[John McCausland]] was a notable [[brigadier general]] in the [[Confederate States Army]] during the Civil War. He was the son of an Irish immigrant.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nHowever, [[conscription]] was resisted by many Irish as an imposition.<ref name=\"Christian G. Samito 2009\"/><ref name=\"Susanna J. Ural 2006\"/> Two years into the war, the conscription law was passed in 1863, and [[New York City draft riots|major draft riots]] erupted in New York. It coincided with the efforts of the city's dominant political machine, [[Tammany Hall]], to enroll Irish immigrants as citizens so they could vote in local elections.<ref>Kevin Kenny, ''The American Irish: A History'' (2-14) p 68</ref>  Many such immigrants suddenly discovered they were now expected to fight for their new country.<ref>William V. Shannon, ''The American Irish: a political and social portrait'' (1989), pp 57\u201359.</ref>  The Irish, employed primarily as laborers, were usually unable to afford the $300 \"commutation fee\" to procure a replacement for service.<ref>Adrian Cook, ''The Armies of the Streets: The New York City Draft Riots of 1863'' (1982) ch 1.</ref> Many of the Irish viewed blacks as competition for scarce jobs, and as the reason why the Civil War was being fought.<ref>Baker, Kevin (March 2003). \"[http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/2003/1/2003_1_17.shtml Violent City] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019000238/http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/2003/1/2003_1_17.shtml |date=2010-10-19 }}\" ''[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]''.</ref> African Americans who fell into the mob's hands were often beaten or killed.<ref name=\"Leslie M 2003\">Leslie M. Harris, ''In the Shadow of Slavery: African Americans in New York City, 1626\u20131863'', University of Chicago Press; 1 edition (February 2, 2003)</ref><ref>{{Cite book| author = Leslie M. Harris | chapter = The New York City Draft Riots of 1863 | title = In the Shadow of Slavery: African Americans in New York City, 1626\u20131863 | chapter-url = http://www.press.uchicago.edu/Misc/Chicago/317749.html | pages = 279\u2013288 | publisher = University of Chicago Press | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-0-226-31773-1}}</ref> The Colored Orphan Asylum on Fifth Avenue, which provided shelter for hundreds of children, was attacked by a mob. It was seen as a \"symbol of white charity to blacks and of black upward mobility,\" reasons enough for its destruction at the hands of a predominantly Irish mob which looked upon African Americans as direct social and economic competitors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1863/07/14/news/mob-new-york-resistance-draft-rioting-bloodshed-conscription-offices-sacked.html?pagewanted=all|title=THE MOB IN NEW YORK; Resistance to the Draft--Rioting and Bloodshed.|last=|first=|date=July 14, 1863|work=The New York Times|access-date=2016-12-19|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref> Fortunately, the largely Irish-American police force was able to secure the orphanage for enough time to allow orphans to escape.<ref name=\"Leslie M 2003\"/><ref>{{cite web\n| title = Riots in New York\n| url = http://www.sonofthesouth.net/leefoundation/civil-war/1863/august/riots-in-new-york.htm\n| work = Civil War Harper's Weekly, August 1, 1863\n| publisher = SonoftheSouth.net\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the Confederacy, many Irish were initially reluctant to support secession; most of them voted for Stephen Douglas in the 1860 presidential election.{{or|date=January 2020}} However several bishops{{who?|date=January 2020}} were enthusiastic supporters of the Confederacy,{{cn|date=January 2020}} and the Irish volunteered for service.{{cn|date=January 2020}} Gleeson wrote that they had higher desertion rates than non-Irish, and sometimes switched sides, suggesting that their support for the Confederacy was tepid.<ref>David T. Gleeson, ''The Green and the Gray: The Irish and the Confederate States of America'' (2013)</ref> During Reconstruction, however, they{{who|date=November 2018}} took a strong position in favor of [[white supremacy]], and they played major roles in attacking blacks in riots in Memphis and New Orleans.<ref>{{cite journal |jstor=3787286 |title=Community, Class and Race in the Memphis Riot of 1866 |journal=Journal of Social History |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=233\u2013246 |last1=Waller |first1=Altina L. |year=1984 |doi=10.1353/jsh/18.2.233}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |jstor=4230742 |title=The New Orleans Riot of 1866, Reconsidered |journal=Louisiana History: The Journal of the Louisiana Historical Association |volume=5 |issue=1 |pages=5\u201327 |last1=Reynolds |first1=Donald E. |year=1964}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |jstor=4231869 |title=Race and Violence in Reconstruction New Orleans: The 1868 Riot |journal=Louisiana History: The Journal of the Louisiana Historical Association |volume=20 |issue=1 |pages=77\u201391 |last1=Hennessey |first1=Melinda Meek |year=1979}}</ref>\n\nIn 1871, New York's [[Orange Riots]] broke out when Irish Protestants celebrated the British victory at the [[Battle of the Boyne]] by parading through Irish Catholic neighborhoods, taunting the residents who then responded with violence.  Police Superintendent James J. Kelso, a Protestant, ordered the parade cancelled as a threat to public safety. Kelso was overruled by the governor, who ordered 5000 militia to protect the marchers.<ref>{{cite book |author=Stephen Albert Rohs |title=Eccentric Nation: Irish Performance in Nineteenth-century New York City |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P-VPcr2sJbcC&pg=PA153 |publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson University Press |year=2009 |page=153 |isbn=9780838641385}}</ref> The Catholics attacked but were stopped by the militia and police, who opened fire killing about 63 Catholics.<ref>{{cite book |author=Michael Allen Gordon |title=The Orange Riots: Irish Political Violence in New York City, 1870 and 1871 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GOZmKrjbSxsC&pg=PA1 |year=1993 |publisher=[[Cornell University Press]] |pages=1\u20132 |isbn=978-0801427541}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Twist-British-Tail.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.45|U.S. President [[Grover Cleveland]] twisting the tail of the British Lion as Americans cheer in the [[Venezuelan crisis of 1895]]; cartoon in ''Puck'' by J.S. Pughe]]\nRelations between the U.S. and Britain were chilly during the 1860s as Americans resented British and [[Canada|Canadian]] support for the Confederacy during the Civil War. After the war American authorities looked the other way as Irish Catholic \"[[Fenian]]s\" plotted and even attempted an invasion of Canada.<ref>Niall Whelehan, ''The Dynamiters: Irish Nationalism and Political Violence in the Wider World, 1867\u20131900'' (Cambridge, 2012)</ref> The Fenians proved a failure,{{how?|date=January 2020}} but Irish Catholic politicians, a growing power in the [[History of the United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]], demanded more independence for Ireland and made anti-British rhetoric\u2014called \"twisting the lion's tail\"\u2014a staple of election campaign appeals to the Irish Catholic vote.<ref>{{cite book| author=Michael J. Hogan| title=Paths to Power: The Historiography of American Foreign Relations to 1941| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rcKEwnVi_IYC&pg=PA76| year=2000| publisher=Cambridge U.P.| page=76| isbn=9780521664134}}</ref>\n\n[[File:TheUsualIrishWayofDoingThings (cr).jpg|thumb|American political cartoon by [[Thomas Nast]] titled \"The Usual Irish Way of Doing Things\", depicting a drunken Irishman lighting a powder keg and swinging a bottle. Published 2 September 1871 in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]'']] A second wave of post-famine Irish immigration, resulting largely from a changing rural economy and the lure of high-paying jobs in America, continued from 1855 to 1921, when the [[Emergency Quota Act|Emergency Immigration Acts of 1921]] and [[Immigration Act of 1924|1924]] imposed a \"quota system\" that significantly limited immigration.{{cn|date=January 2020}} These later immigrants mostly settled in industrial towns and cities of the [[Northeastern United States|Northeast]] and [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]] where Irish American neighborhoods had previously been established.<ref>Nicholsen, Michael D. ''\"Auld Sod\" and the New Turf: Entertainment, Nationalism, and Identity in the Irish Traditional Music Community of Chicago, 1868\u20131999''. Ann Arbor, Michigan: ProQuest, 2007. (pg. 91) {{ISBN|0549400508}}</ref><ref>Byrne, James Patrick, Philip Coleman, Jason Francis King, ed. ''Ireland and the Americas: Culture, Politics, and History''. Vol. 1. Santa Barbara, California: ABC-CLIO, 2008. (pg. 31-34) {{ISBN|1-85109-614-0}}</ref>\n\nThe Irish were having a huge impact on America as a whole. In 1910, there were more people in New York City of Irish ancestry than [[Dublin]]'s whole population, and even today, many of these cities still retain a substantial Irish-American community.<ref>Chisholm, Hugh, ed. \"New York (City)\". ''The Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica''. 11th ed. Vol. XIX. New York: Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Company, 1911. p. 617</ref> Mill towns such as [[Lawrence, Massachusetts|Lawrence]], [[Lowell, Massachusetts|Lowell]], and [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]] attracted many single Irish women as workers in particular.{{cn|date=January 2020}} The [[anthracite]] [[Coal Region]] of northeastern [[Pennsylvania]] saw a massive influx of Irish during this time period; abuses by owners eventually gave rise to resistance groups such as the [[Molly Maguires]].{{cn|date=January 2020}} The best urban economic opportunities for unskilled Irish women and men included \"factory and millwork, domestic service, and the physical labor of public work projects.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Diner |first=Hasia R. |title=Erin's Daughters |page=40}}</ref>\n\nDuring the mid-1900s, Irish immigration to the United States began to decrease. During the years of 1941\u20131950 there were only 1,000,000 immigrants in total, and only 68,151 of them came from Ireland.{{cn|date=January 2020}} These immigrants from Ireland were coming to the U.S. for the same reasons as those before them; they came looking for jobs.<ref>Brownstone, David M., and Irene M. Franck. ''Facts about American Immigration''. New York: H.W. Wilson, 2001. 32+.</ref>\n\n==Social history in the United States==\n===Religion and society===\nReligion has been important to the Irish American identity in America, and continues to play a major role in their communities. Surveys conducted since the 1970s have shown consistent majorities or pluralities of those who self-identify as being of Irish ancestry in the United States as also self-identifying as Protestants.<ref name=\"Carroll 2006 p. 25\" /><ref name=\"RNS 3-17-2014\" /> The Protestants' ancestors arrived primarily in the colonial era, while Catholics are primarily descended from immigrants of the 19th century. Irish leaders have been prominent in the Catholic Church in the United States for over 150 years. The Irish have been leaders in the [[Presbyterian]] and [[Methodism#United States|Methodist]] traditions, as well.<ref name=carroll>{{cite journal |first=Michael P. |last=Carroll |title=How the Irish Became Protestant in America |journal=Religion and American Culture |year=2006 |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=25\u201354 |doi=10.1525/rac.2006.16.1.25}}</ref>\n\nSurveys in the 1990s show that of Americans who identify themselves as \"Irish\", 51% said they were Protestant and 36% identified as Catholic. In the South, Protestants account for 73% of those claiming Irish origins, while Catholics account for 19%. In the North, 45% of those claiming Irish origin are Catholic, while 39% are Protestant.<ref name=carroll /> Many [[African American]]s and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]s claim Irish Protestant or Scots-Irish ancestry.<ref>{{cite book|title=Scotch Irish Foodways in America: Recipes from History|author=M.M. Drymon|page=41}}</ref>\n\n====Irish Catholic and Ulster Protestant relations====\n{{details|Orange Institution|Anti-Catholicism in the United States|Anti-Protestantism}}\nBetween 1607 and 1820, the majority of emigrants from Ireland to America were Protestants<ref>{{cite book | last = Brighton | first = Stephen A.| title = Historical Archaeology of the Irish Diaspora: A Transnational Approach| publisher=University of Tennessee Press| year = 2009 | page = 41 | isbn = 978-1-57233-667-4}}</ref> who were described simply as \"Irish\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Falley | first = Margaret Dicknson| title = Irish and Scotch-Irish Ancestral Research: A Guide to the Genealogical Records | publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company| year = 1995 | page = 12 | isbn = 978-0-8063-0916-3}}</ref> The religious distinction became important after 1820,<ref>{{cite book | last = McCaffrey | first = Lawrence John | title = The Irish Catholic Diaspora in America | publisher = Catholic University of America Press | year = 1998 | page = [https://archive.org/details/irishcatholicdia00mcca/page/5 5] | isbn = 978-0-8132-0896-1 | url = https://archive.org/details/irishcatholicdia00mcca/page/5 }}</ref> when large numbers of Irish Catholics began to emigrate to the United States. Some of the descendants of the colonial Irish Protestant settlers from [[Ulster]] began thereafter to redefine themselves as \"Scotch Irish\", to stress their historic origins, and distanced themselves from Irish Catholics;<ref>{{cite journal |quote=This growing 'division of the mind' between Irish Catholics and Protestants is often noted by Irish historians |first=David T. |last=Gleeson |title='Scotch Irish' and 'Real Irish' in the Nineteenth-century American South |journal=New Hibernia Review |volume=10 |issue=2 |year=2006 |pages=68\u201391 |doi= 10.1353/nhr.2006.0037}}</ref> others continued to call themselves Irish, especially in areas of the South which saw little Irish Catholic immigration. By 1830, Irish diaspora demographics had changed rapidly, with over 60% of all Irish settlers in the US being Catholics from rural areas of Ireland.<ref>{{cite book | last = Brighton | first = Stephen A.| title = Historical Archaeology of the Irish Diaspora: A Transnational Approach| publisher=University of Tennessee Press| year = 2009 | page = 43 | isbn = 978-1-57233-667-4}}</ref>\n\nSome Protestant Irish immigrants became active in explicitly anti-Catholic organizations such as the [[Orange Institution]] and the [[American Protective Association]]. However, participation in the Orange Institution was never as large in the United States as it was in Canada.<ref name=\"Millar191\">{{cite book |first=Kerby A. |last=Millar |title=Emigrants and Exiles |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |year=1988 |page=[https://archive.org/details/emigrantsexiles00kerb_0/page/191 191] |isbn=978-0-19-505187-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/emigrantsexiles00kerb_0/page/191 }}</ref> In the early nineteenth century, the post-Revolutionary [[republicanism|republican]] spirit of the new United States attracted exiled [[United Irishmen]] such as [[Wolfe Tone|Theobald Wolf Tone]] and others, with the presidency of [[Andrew Jackson]] exemplifying this attitude.<ref>{{cite book |first=Kerby A. |last=Millar |title=Emigrants and Exiles |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |year=1988 |page=[https://archive.org/details/emigrantsexiles00kerb_0/page/186 186] |isbn=978-0-19-505187-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/emigrantsexiles00kerb_0/page/186 }}</ref> Most Protestant Irish immigrants in the first several decades of the nineteenth century were those who held to the republicanism of the 1790s, and who were unable to accept Orangeism. Loyalists and Orangemen made up a minority of Irish Protestant immigrants to the United States during this period. Most of the Irish loyalist emigration was bound for [[Upper Canada]] and the Canadian [[Maritime provinces]], where Orange lodges were able to flourish under the British flag.<ref name=\"Millar191\" />\n\nBy 1870, when there were about 930 Orange lodges in the Canadian province of [[Ontario]], there were only 43 in the entire eastern United States. These few American lodges were founded by newly arriving Protestant Irish immigrants in coastal cities such as Philadelphia and New York.<ref>{{cite book |first=Donald |last=McRaild |title=Faith, Fraternity, and Fighting |publisher=Liverpool University Press |year=2005 |page=298 |isbn=978-0-85323-939-0}}</ref> These ventures were short-lived and of limited political and social impact, although there were specific instances of violence involving Orangemen between Catholic and Protestant Irish immigrants, such as the [[Orange Riots]] in New York City in 1824, 1870 and 1871.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=McRaild \n |first=Donald \n |title=The Orange Order, Militant Protestantism and anti-Catholicism: A Bibliographical Essay \n |url=http://ics01.ds.leeds.ac.uk/papers/vp01.cfm?outfit=ids&folder=16&paper=19 \n |accessdate=23 October 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401022714/http://ics01.ds.leeds.ac.uk/papers/vp01.cfm?outfit=ids&folder=16&paper=19 \n |archivedate=1 April 2012 \n}}</ref>\n\nThe first \"Orange riot\" on record was in 1824, in [[Abingdon Square Park|Abingdon Square]], New York, resulting from a 12 July march. Several Orangemen were arrested and found guilty of inciting the riot. According to the State prosecutor in the court record, \"the Orange celebration was until then unknown in the country.\" The immigrants involved were admonished: \"In the United States the oppressed of all nations find an asylum, and all that is asked in return is that they become law-abiding citizens. Orangemen, Ribbonmen, and United Irishmen are alike unknown. They are all entitled to protection by the laws of the country.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=History of the Orange Riots in New York |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 12, 1871 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1871/07/12/archives/history-of-the-orange-riots-in-newyork.html}}</ref>\n[[File:Orange Riot 1871 crop.jpg|thumb|right|The Orange riot of 1871 as depicted in ''[[Frank Leslie's Illustrated Newspaper]]''. The view is at [[25th Street (Manhattan)|25th Street]] in [[Manhattan]] looking south down [[Eighth Avenue (Manhattan)|Eighth Avenue]].]]\nThe later [[Orange Riots]] of 1870 and 1871 killed nearly 70 people, and were fought out between Irish Protestant and Catholic immigrants. After this the activities of the Orange Order were banned for a time, the Order dissolved, and most members joined [[Freemasonry|Masonic]] orders. After 1871, there were no more riots between Irish Catholics and Protestants.<ref>{{cite book |first=Michael |last=Gordon |title=The Orange Riots: Irish Political Violence in New York City, 1870 and 1871 |location=Ithaca, NY |publisher=Cornell University Press |year=1993 |page=221 |isbn=978-0-8014-2754-1}}</ref>\n\nAmerica offered a new beginning, and \"...most descendents of the Ulster Presbyterians of the eighteenth century and even many new Protestant Irish immigrants turned their backs on all associations with Ireland and melted into the American Protestant mainstream.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Timothy |last=Meagher |title=The Columbia Guide to Irish American History |publisher=Columbia University Press |location=New York |year=2005 |pages=91\u201392 |isbn=978-0-231-12070-8}}</ref>\n\n====Catholics====\nIrish priests (especially [[Dominican Order|Dominicans]], [[Franciscan]]s, [[Augustinians]] and [[Order of Friars Minor Capuchin|Capuchins]]) came to the large cities of the East in the 1790s, and when new dioceses were erected in 1808 the [[R. Luke Concanen|first bishop of New York]] was an Irishman in recognition of the contribution of the early Irish clergy.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Thomas T. |last=McAvoy |title=The Irish Clergyman in the United States |journal=American Catholic Studies |year=1964 |volume=75 |issue=1 |pages=6\u201338 |doi=}}</ref>\n[[File:Riots1844staugestine.jpg|thumb|St. Augustine's Church on fire. Anti-Irish, anti-Catholic [[Philadelphia Nativist Riots|Nativist riots]] in Philadelphia in 1844.]]\n \t\n[[Saint Patrick's Battalion]] (''San Patricios'') was a group of several hundred immigrant soldiers, the majority Irish, who deserted the U.S. Army during the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] because of ill treatment or sympathetic leanings to fellow Mexican Catholics. They joined the Mexican army.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2008-03-09-stpatrick_N.htm| title=Bagpipers honor Irish who fought for Mexico| newspaper=[[USA Today]]| date=10 March 2008| first=Chris | last=Hawley}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Boston]] between 1810 and 1840 there had been serious tensions between the bishop and the laity who wanted to control the local parishes. By 1845, the Catholic population in Boston had increased to 30,000 from around 5,000 in 1825, due to the influx of Irish immigrants. With the appointment of John B. Fitzpatrick as bishop in 1845, tensions subsided as the increasingly Irish Catholic community grew to support Fitzpatrick's assertion of the bishop's control of parish government.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Ronald D. |last=Patkus |title=Conflict in the Church and the City: The Problem of Catholic Parish Government in Boston, 1790\u20131865 |journal=Historical Journal of Massachusetts |year=2001 |volume=29 |issue=1 |pages=53\u201376 |doi=}}</ref>\n[[File:Sanpatricioshang.jpg|thumb|left|The mass hanging of Irish Catholic soldiers who joined the Mexican army]]\n\nIn New York, Archbishop [[John Hughes (archbishop of New York)|John Hughes]] (1797\u20131864), an Irish immigrant himself, was deeply involved in \"the Irish question\"\u2014[[Irish nationalism|Irish independence from British rule]]. Hughes supported [[Daniel O'Connell]]'s [[Catholic emancipation]] movement in Ireland, but rejected such radical and violent societies as the [[Young Ireland]]ers and the [[Fenian Brotherhood|National Brotherhood]]. Hughes also disapproved of American Irish radical fringe groups, urging immigrants to assimilate themselves into American life while remaining patriotic to Ireland \"only individually\".<ref>[[John R. G. Hassard|Hassard, John R. G.]] ''Life of the Most Reverend John Hughes, D.D., First Archbishop of New York''. Vol. 4. New York: D. Appleton and Company, 1866. (pg 312)</ref> In Hughes's view, a large-scale movement to form Irish settlements in the western United States was too [[isolationist]] and ultimately detrimental to immigrants' success in the New World.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Charles P. |last=Connor |title=Archbishop Hughes and the Question of Ireland, 1829\u20131862 |journal=Records of the American Catholic Historical Society of Philadelphia |year=1984 |volume=95 |issue=1\u20134 |pages=15\u201326 |doi=}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1840s, Hughes crusaded for public-funded Irish Schools modeled after the successful [[Education in the Republic of Ireland|Irish public school system]] in [[Lowell, Massachusetts]]. Hughes denounced the Public School Society of New York as an extension of an Old-World struggle whose outcome was directed not by understanding of the basic problems but, rather, by mutual mistrust and violently inflamed emotions. For Irish Catholics, the motivation lay largely in memory of British oppression, while their antagonists were dominated by the English Protestant historic fear of papal interference in civil affairs. Because of the vehemence of this quarrel, the [[New York Legislature]] passed the Maclay Act in 1842, giving New York City an elective Board of Education empowered to build and supervise schools and distribute the education fund\u2014but with the proviso that none of the money should go to schools which taught religion. Hughes responded by building an elaborate [[parochial school]] system that stretched to the college level, setting a policy followed in other large cities. Efforts to get city or state funding failed because of vehement Protestant opposition to a system that rivaled the public schools.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Joseph J. |last=McCadden |title=New York's School Crisis of 1840\u20131842: Its Irish Antecedents |journal=Thought |year=1966 |volume=41 |issue=163 |pages=561\u2013588 |doi= 10.5840/thought196641444}}</ref>\n\nIn the west, Catholic Irish were having a large effect as well. The open west attracted many Irish immigrants. Many of these immigrants were Catholic. When they migrated west, they would form \"little pockets\" with other Irish immigrants.<ref name=\":0\" /> Irish Catholic communities were made in \"supportive, village style neighborhoods centered around a Catholic church and called 'parishes'\".<ref name=\":0\" /> These neighborhoods affected the overall lifestyle and atmosphere of the communities. Other ways religion played a part in these towns was the fact that many were started by Irish Catholic priests. Father Bernard Donnelly started \"Town of Kansas\" which would later become Kansas City. His influence over early stages Kansas City was great, and so the Catholic religion was spread to other settlers who arrived.<ref name=\":0\" /> While not all settlers became Catholics, a great number of the early settlers were Catholic. In other western communities, Irish priests wanted to convert the Native Americans to Catholicism.<ref name=\":0\" /> These Catholic Irish would contribute not only to the growth of Catholic population in America, but to the values and traditions in America. \n[[File:69th New York at church.jpg|thumb|Officers and men of the [[Irish-Catholic]] [[69th Infantry Regiment (New York)|69th New York Volunteer Regiment]] attend church services at [[Fort Corcoran]] in 1861.]]\n\n[[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] established a network of colleges in major cities, including [[Boston College]], [[Fordham University]] in New York, and [[Georgetown University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] Fordham was founded in 1841 and attracted students from other regions of the United States, and even [[South America]] and the [[Caribbean]]. At first exclusively a [[liberal arts]] institution, it built a science building in 1886, lending more legitimacy to science in the curriculum there. In addition, a three-year [[bachelor of science]] degree was created.<ref>{{Cite book |first=Raymond A. |last=Schroth |title=S.J. Fordham: A History and Memoir |edition=Revised |publisher=Fordham University Press |location=New York |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-8232-2977-2}}</ref> Boston College, by contrast, was established over twenty years later in 1863 to appeal to urban Irish Catholics. It offered a rather limited intellectual curriculum, however, with the priests at Boston College prioritizing spiritual and sacramental activities over intellectual pursuits. One consequence was that [[Harvard Law School]] would not admit Boston College graduates to its law school. Modern Jesuit leadership in American academia was not to become their hallmark across all institutions until the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Marianne |last=Gallagher |title=The Jesuits at Boston College in the Late Nineteenth Century |journal=American Catholic Studies |year=2007 |volume=118 |issue=2 |pages=43\u201366 |doi=}}</ref>\n\nThe Irish became prominent in the leadership of the Catholic Church in the U.S. by the 1850s\u2014by 1890 there were 7.3 million Catholics in the U.S. and growing, and most bishops were Irish.<ref>Kenny (2000), pp. 74\u20135, 163\u201371</ref> As late as the 1970s, when Irish were 17% of American Catholics, they were 35% of the priests and 50% of the bishops, together with a similar proportion of presidents of Catholic colleges and hospitals.<ref>{{Cite book |first=Andrew M. |last=Greeley |title=That Most Distressful Nation: The Taming of the American Irish |year=1972 |location= |page=264 |isbn=978-0-8129-6219-2}}</ref>\n\n====Protestants====\n{{Main|Scotch-Irish Americans}}\n\nThe [[Ulster Scots people|Scots-Irish]] who settled in the back country of colonial America were largely [[Presbyterian]]s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Leyburn |first=James G. |title=The Scots-Irish: A Social History |url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb |url-access=registration |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |year=1962 |page=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/273 273]}}</ref> The establishment of many settlements in the remote back-country put a strain on the ability of the Presbyterian Church to meet the new demand for qualified, college-educated clergy.<ref name=Griffin-164>{{cite book |last=Griffin |first=Patrick |title=The People with No Name: Ireland's Ulster Scots, America's Scots Irish, and the Creation of a British Atlantic World |location= |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=2001 |pages=164\u2013165 |isbn=978-0-691-07461-0}}</ref> Religious groups such as the [[Baptists]] and [[Methodist]]s did not require higher education of their ministers, so they could more readily supply ministers to meet the demand of the growing Scots-Irish settlements.<ref name=Griffin-164/> By about 1810, Baptist and Methodist churches were in the majority, and the descendants of the Scotch-Irish today remain predominantly Baptist or Methodist.<ref>{{cite book |first=James |last=Leyburn |title=The Scotch-Irish |url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb |url-access=registration |publisher=University of North Carolina |year=1962 |page=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/295 295]}}</ref> They were avid participants in the revivals taking place during the [[Great Awakening]] from the 1740s to the 1840s.<ref>Barkan, Elliott Robert, ed. ''A Nation of Peoples: A Sourcebook on America's Multicultural Heritage''. [[Westport, Connecticut]]: Greenwood Publishing Group, 1999. (pg. 79) {{ISBN|0-313-29961-7}}</ref> They take pride in their Irish heritage because they identify with the values ascribed to the Scotch-Irish who played a major role in the American Revolution and in the development of American culture.<ref name=carroll/>\n\n=====Presbyterians=====\nThe first Presbyterian community in America was established in 1640 in Southampton, Long Island New York.<ref>The Presbyterian Historical Society National Archives</ref> [[Francis Makemie]], an [[List of Irish Presbyterians|Irish Presbyterian]] immigrant later established churches in Maryland and Virginia.<ref>{{cite book|title=Making it in America: A Sourcebook on Eminent Ethnic Americans|author=Elliott Robert Barkan|page=214}}</ref> Makemie was born and raised near [[Ramelton]], [[County Donegal]], to [[Ulster Scots people|Ulster Scots]] parents. He was educated in the [[University of Glasgow]] and set out to organize and initiate the construction of several Presbyterian Churches throughout Maryland and Virginia. By 1706, Makemie and his followers constructed  a Presbyterian Church in [[Rehobeth, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Faiths Across Time: 5,000 Years of Religious History|author=J. Gordon Melton|page=1278}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Maryland's colonial Eastern Shore; historical sketches of counties and of some notable structures|author=Earle, Swepson, Skirven, Percy G.|page=53}}</ref> In 1707, after traveling to New York to establish a presbytery, Francis Makemie was charged with preaching without a license by the English immigrant and Governor of New York, [[Edward Hyde, 3rd Earl of Clarendon|Edward Hyde]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Presbyterians and American Culture: A History|author=Bradley J. Longfield|page=2}}</ref> Makemie won a vital victory for the fight of religious freedom for Scots-Irish immigrants when he was acquitted and gained recognition for having \"stood up to Anglican authorities\". Makemie became one of the wealthiest immigrants to colonial America, owning more than 5,000 acres and 33 slaves.<ref>{{cite book|title=Rebels and Renegades: A Chronology of Social and Political Dissent in the United States|author=Neil A. Hamilton|page=24}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Irish Immigrants in the Land of Canaan: Letters and Memoirs from Colonial and Revolutionary America, 1675-1815|author1=Kerby A. Miller |author2=Arnold Schrier |author3=Bruce D. Boling |author4=David N. Doyle |page=110}}</ref>\n\n[[New Light]] Presbyterians founded the College of New Jersey, later renamed [[Princeton University]], in 1746 in order to train ministers dedicated to their views. The college was the educational and religious capital of Scots-Irish America.<ref>{{cite book |first=James G. |last=Leyburn |title=The Scots-Irish: A Social History |url=https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb |url-access=registration |year=1989 |location=Chapel Hill |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/scotchirishsocia0000leyb/page/285 285] |isbn=978-0-8078-4259-1}}</ref> By 1808, loss of confidence in the college within the Presbyterian Church led to the establishment of the separate [[Princeton Theological Seminary]], but deep Presbyterian influence at the college continued through the 1910s, as typified by university president [[Woodrow Wilson]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Thomas J. |last=Wertenbaker |title=The College of New Jersey and the Presbyterian Church |journal=Journal of Presbyterian History |year=1998 |volume=76 |issue=1 |pages=31\u201335 |doi=}}</ref>\n\nOut on the frontier, the Scots-Irish Presbyterians of the [[Muskingum River|Muskingum Valley]] in [[Ohio]] established [[Muskingum College]] at [[New Concord, Ohio|New Concord]] in 1837. It was led by two clergymen, Samuel Wilson and Benjamin Waddle, who served as trustees, president, and professors during the first few years. During the 1840s and 1850s the college survived the rapid turnover of very young presidents who used the post as a stepping stone in their clerical careers, and in the late 1850s it weathered a storm of student protest. Under the leadership of L. B. W. Shryock during the Civil War, Muskingum gradually evolved from a local and locally controlled institution to one serving the entire Muskingum Valley. It is still affiliated with the Presbyterian church.<ref>{{cite journal |first=William L. |last=Fisk |title=The Early Years of Muskingum College |journal=Old Northwest |year=1979 |volume=5 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201344 |doi=}}</ref>\n\nBrought up in a Scots-Irish Presbyterian home, [[Cyrus McCormick]] of Chicago developed a strong sense of devotion to the Presbyterian Church. Throughout his later life, he used the wealth gained through invention of the [[mechanical reaper]] to further the work of the church. His benefactions were responsible for the establishment in Chicago of the Presbyterian Theological Seminary of the Northwest (after his death renamed the [[McCormick Theological Seminary]] of the Presbyterian Church). He assisted the [[Union Presbyterian Seminary]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]]. He also supported a series of religious publications, beginning with the ''Presbyterian Expositor'' in 1857 and ending with the ''Interior'' (later called ''The Continent''), which his widow continued until her death.<ref>{{cite journal |first=John Frederick |last=Lyons |title=Cyrus Hall McCormick, Presbyterian Layman |journal=Journal of the Presbyterian Historical Society |year=1961 |volume=39 |issue=1 |pages=14\u201329 |doi=}}</ref>\n\n=====Methodists=====\nIrish immigrants were the first immigrant group to America to build and organize Methodist churches. Many of the early Irish immigrants who did so came from a German-Irish background. [[Barbara Heck]], an Irish woman of German descent from County Limerick, Ireland, immigrated to America in 1760, with her husband, Paul. She is often considered to be the \"Mother of American Methodism.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=In Our Own Voices: Four Centuries of American Women's Religious Writing|author1=Rosemary Skinner Keller |author2=Rosemary Radford Ruether |page=87}}</ref> Heck guided and mentored her cousin, [[Philip Embury]], who was also an \"Irish Palatine\" immigrant.<ref>{{cite book|title=The New York Chronology: The Ultimate Compendium of Events, People, and Anecdotes from the Dutch to the Present|author=James Trager|page=29}}</ref> Heck and Embury constructed the [[John Street Methodist Church]], which today is usually recognized as the oldest Methodist Church in the United States.<ref>{{cite book|title=Guide to New York City Landmarks|author=Matthew A. Postal, Andrew Dolkart, New York Landmarks Preservation Commission|page=14}}</ref> However, another church constructed by prominent Irish Methodist immigrant, [[Robert Strawbridge]], may have preceded the John Street Methodist Church.<ref>{{cite book|title=American Religious Leaders|author=Timothy L. Hall|page=163}}</ref>\n\n====Women====\n[[File:The Irish Vampire - Punch (24 October 1885), 199 - BL.jpg|thumb|Irish Lass depiction in 1885.]]\nThe Irish people were the first of many to immigrate to the U.S. in mass waves, including large groups of single young women between the ages of 16 and 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ww.tenement.org/encyclopedia/irish_immigrants.htm|title=Lower East Side Tenement Museum|website=Tenement.org|access-date=2016-05-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513063925/http://ww.tenement.org/encyclopedia/irish_immigrants.htm|archivedate=2016-05-13}}</ref> Up until this point, free women who settled in the colonies mostly came after their husbands had already made the journey and could afford their trip, or were brought over to be married to an eligible colonist who paid for their journey. Many Irish fled their home country to escape unemployment and starvation during the Great Irish Famine.<ref name=\"historyplace.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.historyplace.com/worldhistory/famine/america.htm|title=The History Place - Irish Potato Famine: Gone to America|website=Historyplace.com|access-date=2016-05-11}}</ref> The richest of the Irish resettled in England, where their skilled work was greatly accepted, but lower class Irish and women could find little work in Western Europe, leading them to cross the Atlantic in search of greater financial opportunities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irish-genealogy-toolkit.com/journey-to-Ellis-Island.html#Arrival|title=The journey to Ellis Island, New York, was made by hundreds of thousands of Irish immigrants|website=Irish-genealogy-toolkit.com|access-date=2016-05-11}}</ref>\n\nSome Irish women resorted to prostitution in large cities such as Boston and New York City. They were often arrested for intoxication, public lewdness, and petty larceny.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ronald H. Bayor|author2=Timothy Meagher|title=The New York Irish|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WfCmS90xyEIC&pg=PA121|year=1997|publisher=JHU Press|page=121|isbn=9780801857645}}</ref>  Most of the single Irish women preferred service labor as a form of income. These women made a higher wage than most by serving the middle and high-class in their own homes as nannies, cooks and cleaners. The wages for domestic service were higher than that of factory workers and they lived in the attics of upscale mansions. By 1870, forty percent of Irish women worked as domestic servants in New York City, making them over fifty percent of the service industry at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tenement.org/encyclopedia/irish_immigrants.htm|title=Lower East Side Tenement Museum|website=Tenement.org|access-date=2016-05-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418064830/https://tenement.org/encyclopedia/irish_immigrants.htm|archivedate=2016-04-18}}</ref>\n\nPrejudices ran deep in the north and could be seen in newspaper cartoons depicting Irish men as hot-headed, violent drunkards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.victoriana.com/history/irish-political-cartoons.html|title=Irish Stereotypes - Stereotyping of the Irish Immigrant (PICTURES)|website=Victoriana.com|access-date=2016-05-11}}</ref> The initial backlash the Irish received in America lead to their self-imposed seclusion, making assimilation into society a long and painful process.<ref name=\"historyplace.com\"/>\n\n====Language====\nDown to the end of the 19th century a large number of Irish immigrants arrived speaking [[Irish language|Irish]] as their first language. This continued to be the case with immigrants from certain counties even in the 20th century. The Irish language was first mentioned as being spoken in North America in the 17th century. Large numbers of Irish emigrated to America throughout the 18th century, bringing the language with them, and it was particularly strong in [[Pennsylvania]].<ref>For the cultural and linguistic context see \u00d3 hAnnrach\u00e1in, Stiof\u00e1n (ed.), 1979. ''Go Meirice\u00e1 Siar''. An Cl\u00f3chomhar Tta, Baile \u00c1tha Cliath; Ihde, Thomas W. (ed.), 1994. ''The Irish Language in the United States: a historical, sociolinguistic and applied linguistic survey''. Bergin & Garvey. {{ISBN|0-89789-331-X}}</ref> It was also  widely spoken in such places as [[New York City]], where it proved a useful recruiting tool for Loyalists during the [[American Revolution]].<ref>Kirby A. Miller, \"Scotch Irish,' 'Black Irish' and 'Real Irish': Emigrants and Identities in the Old South\" in Andy Bielenberg (ed.), ''The Irish Diaspora'', Routledge 2014, lgh 148-9. {{ISBN|978-1138835818}}</ref><ref>Rodgers, Nini, \"The Irish in the Caribbean 1641-1837: An Overview\", IV, ''Irish Migration Studies in Latin America'' [http://www.irishargentine.org/0711rodgers4.htm]</ref>\n\nIrish speakers continued to arrive in large numbers throughout the 19th century, particularly after the Famine. There was a certain amount of literacy in Irish, as shown by the many Irish-language manuscripts which immigrants brought with them. In 1881 ''An Gaodhal'' was founded, being the first newspaper in the world to be largely in Irish. It continued to be published into the 20th century,<ref>The paper and its context are discussed by Fionnuala U\u00ed Fhlannag\u00e1in in: U\u00ed Fhlannag\u00e1in, Fionnuala, 1990. ''M\u00edche\u00e1l \u00d3 L\u00f3ch\u00e1in agus An Gaodhal''. An Cl\u00f3chomhar Tta, Baile \u00c1tha Cliath.</ref> and now has an online successor in ''[[An Gael]]'', an international literary magazine.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jim Norton |url=http://www.angaelmagazine.com/ |title=An Gael - Baile |publisher=Angaelmagazine.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-28}}</ref> A number of Irish immigrant newspapers in the 19th and 20th centuries had Irish language columns.\n\nIrish immigrants fell into three linguistic categories: [[monolingual]] [[Irish language|Irish]] speakers, [[bilingual]] speakers of both Irish and [[English language|English]], and monolingual English speakers.<ref>{{cite book | last = Bayor | first = Ronald H. | authorlink = |author2=Timothy J. Meagher | title = The New York Irish| publisher=The Johns Hopkins University Press | year = 1997 | page = 253 | isbn = 978-0-8018-5764-5}}</ref> Estimates indicate that there were around 400,000 Irish speakers in the United States in the 1890s, located primarily in [[New York City]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Boston]], [[Chicago]] and [[Yonkers, New York|Yonkers]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Bayor | first = Ronald H. | authorlink = |author2=Timothy J. Meagher | title = The New York Irish| publisher=The Johns Hopkins University Press | year = 1997 | page = 254 | isbn = 978-0-8018-5764-5}}</ref> The Irish-speaking population of New York reached its height in this period, when speakers of Irish numbered between 70,000 and 80,000.<ref>{{cite book | last = Bayor | first = Ronald H. | authorlink = |author2=Timothy J. Meagher | title = The New York Irish| publisher=The Johns Hopkins University Press | year = 1997 | page = 274 | isbn = 978-0-8018-5764-5}}</ref> This number declined during the early 20th century, dropping to 40,000 in 1939, 10,000 in 1979, and 5,000 in 1995.<ref><!-- cite book --> Garcia, Ofelia, and Joshua A. Fishman, ed. ''The Multilingual Apple: Language in New York City''. 2nd ed. Berlin and New York: Mouton de Gruyter, 2002. (pg. 67) {{ISBN|3-11-017281-X}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2000 census, the Irish language ranks 66th out of the 322 languages spoken today in the U.S., with over 25,000 speakers. [[New York state]] has the most Irish speakers of the 50 states, and [[Massachusetts]] the highest percentage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Irish Gaelic |url=http://www.usefoundation.org/userdata/file/Research/Languages/irish_gaelic.pdf |publisher=UseFoundation.org |date=2005-01-28 |accessdate=2009-06-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129051111/http://usefoundation.org/userdata/file/Research/Languages/irish_gaelic.pdf |archivedate=2010-11-29 }}</ref>\n\n[[Dalta\u00ed na Gaeilge]], a nonprofit Irish language advocacy group based in [[Elberon, New Jersey]], estimated that about 30,000 people spoke the language in America as of 2006. This, the organization claimed, was a remarkable increase from only a few thousand at the time of the group's founding in 1981.<ref>{{Cite news| last= Gray| first= Patricia Bellew |title='Tis True: Irish Gaelic Still Charms |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9803EEDF1031F931A25750C0A9609C8B63 |work=[[The New York Times]] |page= |pages= |date=2006-04-12 |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref>\n\n===Occupations===\n{{Celts and Modern Celts sidebar}}\nBefore 1800, significant numbers of Irish Protestant immigrants became farmers; many headed to the frontier where land was cheap or free and it was easier to start a farm or herding operation.<ref>Williams, John Alexander. ''Appalachia: A History''. Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press, 2002. (pg. 41-46) {{ISBN|0-8078-5368-2}}</ref> Many Irish Protestants and Catholics alike were [[indentured servant]]s, unable to pay their own passage or sentenced to servitude.<ref>{{cite book| last=Miller| first=Kerby A.| title=Irish immigrants in the land of Canaan letters and memoirs from colonial and revolutionary America, 1675-1815| year=2003| publisher=Oxford University Press| location=Oxford| isbn=9780195348224}}</ref>\n\nAfter 1840, most Irish Catholic immigrants went directly to the cities, [[mill town]]s, and railroad or canal construction sites on the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]]. In [[upstate New York]], the [[Great Lakes]] area, the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]] and the [[American frontier|Far West]], many became farmers or ranchers. In the East, male Irish laborers were hired by Irish contractors to work on canals, railroads, streets, sewers and other construction projects, particularly in [[New York (state)|New York state]] and [[New England]]. The Irish men also worked in these labor positions in the mid-west. They worked to construct towns where there had been none previously. Kansas City was one such town, and eventually became an important cattle town and railroad center.<ref name=\":0\" /> Labor positions weren't the only occupations for Irish, though. Some moved to New England mill towns, such as [[Holyoke, Massachusetts|Holyoke]], [[Lowell, Massachusetts|Lowell]], [[Taunton, Massachusetts|Taunton]], [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton]], [[Fall River, Massachusetts|Fall River]], and [[Milford, Massachusetts]], where owners of textile mills welcomed the new, low-wage workers. They took the jobs previously held by [[Yankee]] women known as [[Lowell girls]].<ref>Hindman, Hugh D. ''Child Labor: An American History''. [[Armonk, New York]]: M.E. Sharpe, 2002. (pg. 28) {{ISBN|0-7656-0936-3}}</ref><ref>Harrell, David Edwin Jr., Edwin S. Gaustad, John B. Boles, Sally Foreman Griffith, and Randall M. Miller. ''Unto a Good Land: A History of the American People to 1900''. [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]]: Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2005. (pg. 300) {{ISBN|0-8028-2944-9}}</ref><ref>Robinson, J. Dennis. ''Striking Back: The Fight to End Child Labor Exploitation''. [[Mankato, Minnesota]]: Compass Point Books, 2010. (pg. 19) {{ISBN|0-7565-4297-9}}</ref> A large percentage of Irish Catholic women took jobs as maids in hotels and private households.<ref name=\"Watkin\">{{cite book |last=Watkin |first=Edward |title=Enter the Irish-American |publisher=[[iUniverse]] |location=Lincoln, NE |year=2002 |pages=47\u201355, 65, 157 |isbn=978-0595227303}}</ref>\n\nLarge numbers of unemployed or very poor Irish Catholics lived in squalid conditions in the new city slums and tenements.<ref name=\"yale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.yale.edu/glc/archive/1021.htm |title=The Sanitary and Moral Condition of New York City |publisher=[[Gilder Lehrman Center for the Study of Slavery, Resistance and Abolition]], [[Yale University]] |accessdate=2008-04-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511202930/http://www.yale.edu/glc/archive/1021.htm |archivedate=2008-05-11}}</ref>\n\nSingle, Irish immigrant women quickly assumed jobs in high demand but for very low pay. The majority of them worked in mills, factories, and private households and were considered the bottommost group in the female job hierarchy, alongside African American women. Workers considered mill work in cotton textiles and needle trades the least desirable because of the dangerous and unpleasant conditions. Factory work was primarily a worst-case scenario for widows or daughters of families already involved in the industry.<ref>{{cite book |last=Diner |first=Hasia R. |title=Erin's Daughters |pages=72, 74\u201376}}</ref> Unlike many other immigrants, Irish women preferred domestic work because it was constantly in great demand among middle- and upper-class American households.<ref>{{cite book |last=Diner |first=Hasia R. |title=Erin's Daughters |page=84}}</ref> Although wages differed across the country, they were consistently higher than those of the other occupations available to Irish women and could often be negotiated because of the lack of competition. Also, the working conditions in well-off households were significantly better than those of factories or mills, and free room and board allowed domestic servants to save money or send it back to their families in Ireland.<ref>{{cite book| last=Diner| first=Hasia R.| title=Erin's Daughters| pages=90\u201393}}</ref>\n\nDespite some of the benefits of domestic work, Irish women's job requirements were difficult and demeaning. Subject to their employers around the clock, Irish women cooked, cleaned, babysat and more. Because most servants lived in the home where they worked, they were separated from their communities. Most of all, the American stigma on domestic work suggested that Irish women were failures who had \"about the same intelligence as that of an old grey-headed negro.\" This quote illustrates how, in a period of extreme [[Racism in the United States|racism]] towards African Americans, society similarly viewed Irish immigrants as inferior beings.<ref>{{cite book| last=Diner| first=Hasia R.| title=Erin's Daughters| page=92}}</ref>\n[[File:Irish immigrants 1909.jpg|thumb|Irish immigrants in [[Kansas City, Missouri]], c. 1909]]\nAlthough the Irish Catholics started very low on the social status scale, by 1900 they had jobs and earnings about equal on average to their neighbors. This was largely due to their ability to speak English when they arrived. The Irish were able to rise quickly within the working world, unlike non-English speaking immigrants.<ref>Funchion, Michael F. ''Ethnic Chicago. A Multicultural Portrait''. Grand Rapids, Michigan: William B. Eerdmans, 1995. Print.</ref> Yet there were still many shanty and lower working class communities in Chicago, Philadelphia, Boston, New York, and other parts of the country.<ref>Kent, Jacob. ''America in 1900''. Armonk, New York: M.E. Sharpe, 2002. (pg. 100) {{ISBN|0-7656-0596-1}}</ref> <!-- This is also referenced in \"The Irish in 1900\" (pg. 90) of Jay P. Dolan's The Irish Americans: A History -->\n\nAfter 1945, the Catholic Irish consistently ranked at the top of the social hierarchy, thanks especially to their high rate of college attendance, and due to that many Irish American men have risen to higher socio-economic table.<ref name=\"greeley1988\">Greeley (1988), p. 1.</ref>\n\n====Local government====\nIn the 19th century, jobs in local government were distributed by politicians to their supporters, and with significant strength in city hall the Irish became candidates for positions in all departments, such as  [[police department]]s, [[fire department]]s, public schools and other [[public service]]s of major cities. In 1897 New York City was formed by consolidating its five boroughs. That created 20,000 new patronage jobs. New York invested heavily in large-scale public works. This produced thousands of unskilled and semi-skilled jobs in subways, street railways, waterworks, and port facilities. Over half the Irish men employed by the city worked in utilities. Across all ethnic groups In New York City, municipal employment grew from  54,000 workers in 1900 to 148,000 in 1930.<ref>{{cite book|author=Roger David Waldinger|title=Still the Promised City?: African-Americans and New Immigrants in Postindustrial New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XIX2w_N2fCkC&pg=PA210|year=1999|publisher=Harvard UP|page=210|isbn=9780674000728}}</ref>  In New York City, Albany, and Jersey City, about one third of the Irish of the first and second generation had municipal jobs in 1900.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jessica Trounstine|title=Political Monopolies in American Cities: The Rise and Fall of Bosses and Reformers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sRI4AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA156|year=2008|publisher=U of Chicago Press|page=156|isbn=9780226812823}}</ref>\n\n====Police====\nBy 1855, according to New York Police Commissioner [[George W. Matsell]] (1811\u20131877),<ref>Newton, Michael. ''The Encyclopedia of American Law Enforcement''. New York: Facts on File, 2007. (pg. 216) {{ISBN|0-8160-6290-0}}</ref> almost 17 percent of the police department's officers were Irish-born (compared to 28.2 percent of the city) in a report to the [[New York City Council|Board of Aldermen]];<ref>James Lardner, and Thomas Reppetto. ''NYPD: A City and Its Police''. (2000)</ref> of the NYPD's 1,149 men, Irish-born officers made up 304 of 431 foreign-born policemen.<ref name=\"Watkin\"/> In the 1860s more than half of those arrested in New York City were Irish born or of Irish descent but nearly half of the city's law enforcement officers were also Irish. By the turn of the 20th century, five out of six NYPD officers were Irish born or of Irish descent. As late as the 1960s, 42% of the NYPD were Irish Americans.<ref>Richard Bessel, and Clive Emsley. ''Patterns of Provocation: Police and Public Disorder''. (2000) p. 87</ref>\n\nUp to the 20th and early 21st century, Irish Catholics continue to be prominent in the law enforcement community, especially in the Northeastern United States. The [[Emerald Society]], an Irish American fraternal organization, was founded in 1953 by the NYPD.<ref>Ruff, Joshua and Michael Cronin. ''Images of America: New York City Police''. [[Charleston, South Carolina]]: Arcadia Publishing, 2012. (pg. 96) {{ISBN|0-7385-7636-0}}</ref> When the Boston chapter of the Emerald Society formed in 1973, half of the [[Boston Police Department|city's police officers]] became members.\n\n====Teachers====\nTowards the end of the 19th century, schoolteaching became the most desirable occupation for the second generation of female Irish immigrants. Teaching was similar to domestic work for the first generation of Irish immigrants in that it was a popular job and one that relied on a woman's decision to remain unmarried.<ref>{{cite book| last=Diner| first=Hasia R.| title=Erin's Daughters |page=96}}</ref> The disproportionate number of Irish-American Catholic women who entered the job market as teachers in the late 19th century and early 20th century from Boston to San Francisco was a beneficial result of the Irish [[National school (Ireland)|National school]] system. Irish schools prepared young single women to support themselves in a new country, which inspired them to instill the importance of education, college training, and a profession in their American-born daughters even more than in their sons. Evidence from schools in New York City illustrate the upward trend of Irish women as teachers: \"as early as 1870, twenty percent of all schoolteachers were Irish women, and...by 1890 Irish females comprised two-thirds of those in the Sixth Ward schools.\" Irish women attained admirable reputations as schoolteachers, which enabled some to pursue professions of even higher stature.<ref>{{cite book| last=Diner| first=Hasia R.| title=Erin's Daughters| pages=97\u201399}}</ref>\n\n====Nuns====\nUpon arrival in the United States, many Irish women became [[nun|Catholic nuns]] and participated in the many American sisterhoods, especially those in [[St. Louis]] in Missouri, [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]] in Minnesota, and [[Troy, New York|Troy]] in New York. Additionally, the women who settled in these communities were often sent back to Ireland to recruit. This kind of religious lifestyle appealed to Irish female immigrants because they outnumbered their male counterparts and the Irish cultural tendency to postpone marriage often promoted gender separation and celibacy. Furthermore, \"the Catholic church, clergy, and women religious were highly respected in Ireland,\" making the sisterhoods particularly attractive to Irish immigrants.<ref>{{cite book| last=Coburn| first=Carol K.| title=Spirited Lives: How Nuns Shaped Catholic Culture and American Life, 1836\u20131920| url=https://archive.org/details/spiritedliveshow3620cobu| url-access=registration| year=1999| publisher=The University of North Carolina Press| location=Chapel Hill| pages=[https://archive.org/details/spiritedliveshow3620cobu/page/87 87\u201389]}}</ref> Nuns provided extensive support for Irish immigrants in large cities, especially in fields such as nursing and teaching but also through orphanages, widows' homes, and housing for young, single women in domestic work.<ref>{{cite book| last=Coburn| first=Carol K.| title=Spirited Lives| pages=210\u2013211}}</ref> Although many Irish communities built parish schools run by nuns, the majority of Irish parents in large cities in the East enrolled their children in the public school system, where daughters or granddaughters of Irish immigrants had already established themselves as teachers.<ref>{{cite book| last=Coburn| first=Carol K.| title=Spirited Lives| pages=140\u2013141}}</ref>\n\n===Discrimination===\n[[File:No Irish Need Apply (lyric sheet).jpg|thumb|upright|1862 song that used the \"No Irish Need Apply\" slogan. It was copied from a similar London song.<ref name=\"jensen\">{{Cite journal|last=Jensen |first=Richard |year=2002 |title='No Irish Need Apply': A Myth of Victimization |journal=Journal of Social History |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=405\u2013429 |url=http://tigger.uic.edu/~rjensen/no-irish.htm |accessdate=2008-11-07 |quote= |doi=10.1353/jsh.2003.0021}}</ref>]]\nCatholics and Protestants kept their distance; intermarriage between Catholics and Protestants was uncommon, and strongly discouraged by both Protestant ministers and Catholic priests. As Dolan notes, \"'Mixed marriages', as they were called, were allowed in rare cases, were warned against repeatedly, and were uncommon.\"<ref>Jay P. Dolan, ''The American Catholic Experience'' (1985) p. 228</ref> Rather, intermarriage was primarily with other ethnic groups who shared their religion. Irish Catholics, for example, would commonly intermarry with German Catholics or Poles in the Midwest and Italians in the Northeast.\n\nIrish-American journalists \"scoured the cultural landscape for evidence of insults directed at the Irish in America.\" Much of what historians know about hostility to the Irish comes from their reports in Irish and in Democratic newspapers.<ref>Mick Mulcrone,  \"The Famine Irish and the Irish-American Press: Strangers in a Hostile Land.\" ''American Journalism'' 20#3 (2003) pp 49-72, quote p 62</ref>\n\nWhile the parishes were struggling to build parochial schools, many Catholic children attended public schools. The Protestant [[King James Version]] of the Bible was widely used in public schools, but Catholics were forbidden by their church from reading or reciting from it.<ref>According to [[canon law]], Catholics were prohibited from reading Bibles published by non-Catholics. Charles Augustine, ''A Commentary on the New Code of Canon Law'' (1921) v. 6 p. 467</ref>  Many Irish children complained that Catholicism was openly mocked in the classroom. In New York City, the curriculum vividly portrayed Catholics, and specifically the Irish, as villainous.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/kcet/publicschool/innovators/hughes.html |title=John Joseph Hughes (1797-1864) |year=2001 |work=SCHOOL: The Story of American Public Education |publisher=[[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS.org]] |accessdate=27 June 2011}}</ref> The Catholic archbishop [[John Hughes (archbishop of New York)|John Hughes]], an immigrant to America from County Tyrone, Ireland, campaigned for public funding of [[History of Catholic education in the United States|Catholic education]] in response to the bigotry. While never successful in obtaining public money for private education, the debate with the city's Protestant elite spurred by Hughes' passionate campaign paved the way for the secularization of public education nationwide. In addition, [[List of Roman Catholic universities and colleges in the United States|Catholic higher education]] expanded during this period with colleges and universities that evolved into such institutions as [[Fordham University]] and [[Boston College]] providing alternatives to Irish who were not otherwise permitted to apply to other colleges.\n\n[[File:NINA-nyt.JPG|thumb|left|''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' want ad 1854\u2014the only ''New York Times'' ad with NINA for men.]]\nPrejudice against Irish Catholics in the U.S. reached a peak in the mid-1850s with the [[Know Nothing]] Movement, which tried to oust Catholics from public office. After a year or two of local success, the Know Nothing Party vanished.<ref>Dolan, ''The Irish Americans'' (2008) pp 97-98</ref> Some historians, however, maintain that actual job discrimination was minimal.<ref name=\"jensen\"/>\n\nMany Irish work gangs were hired by contractors to build canals, railroads, city streets and sewers across the country.<ref name=\"Watkin\"/> In the South, they underbid slave labor.<ref>Corbett, Katharine T. ''In Her Place: A Guide to St. Louis Women's History''. St. Louis: Missouri History Museum, 2000. (pg. 79) {{ISBN|1-883982-30-8}}</ref> One result was that small cities that served as railroad centers came to have large Irish populations.<ref>Sisson, Richard, Christian K. Zacher and Andrew Robert Lee Cayton, ed. ''The American Midwest: An Interpretive Encyclopedia''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 2007. (pg. 1089) {{ISBN|0-253-34886-2}}</ref>\n\nIn 1895, the [[Knights of Equity]] was founded, to combat discrimination against Irish Catholics in the U.S., and to assist them financially when needed.\n\n====Stereotypes====\nIrish Catholics were popular targets for stereotyping in the 19th century. According to historian George Potter, the media often stereotyped the Irish in America as being boss-controlled, violent (both among themselves and with those of other ethnic groups), voting illegally, prone to [[alcoholism]] and dependent on street gangs that were often violent or criminal. Potter quotes contemporary newspaper images:\n\n<blockquote>You will scarcely ever find an Irishman dabbling in counterfeit money, or breaking into houses, or swindling; but if there is any fighting to be done, he is very apt to have a hand in it.\" Even though Pat might \"'meet with a friend and for love knock him down,'\" noted a [[Montreal]] paper, the fighting usually resulted from a sudden excitement, allowing there was \"but little 'malice prepense' in his whole composition.\" The ''Catholic Telegraph'' of [[Cincinnati]] in 1853, saying that the \"name of 'Irish' has become identified in the minds of many, with almost every species of outlawry,\" distinguished the Irish vices as \"not of a deep malignant nature,\" arising rather from the \"transient burst of undisciplined passion,\" like \"drunk, disorderly, fighting, etc., not like robbery, cheating, swindling, counterfeiting, slandering, calumniating, blasphemy, using obscene language, &c.<ref name=\"potter526\">Potter (1960), p. 526.</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Joseph F. Keppler - Uncle Sam's lodging-house.jpg|thumb|1882 illustration from ''Puck''  depicting Irish immigrants as troublemakers, as compared to those of other nationalities]]\n\nThe Irish had many humorists of their own, but were scathingly attacked in political cartoons, especially those in [[Puck (magazine)|''Puck'']] magazine from the 1870s to 1900; it was edited by secular Germans who opposed the Catholic Irish in politics. In addition, the cartoons of [[Thomas Nast]] were especially hostile; for example, he depicted the Irish-dominated [[Tammany Hall]] machine in New York City as a ferocious tiger.<ref name=\"NDE\">{{cite web| url = http://www.nde.state.ne.us/SS/irish/unit_2.html | title = Irish Famine: Racism | publisher = Nebraska Department of Education | accessdate = 2008-04-14 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080331000610/http://www.nde.state.ne.us/SS/irish/unit_2.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-03-31}}</ref>\n\nThe stereotype of the Irish as violent drunks has lasted well beyond its high point in the mid-19th century. For example, President [[Richard Nixon]] once told advisor [[Charles Colson]] that \"[t]he Irish have certain \u2014 for example, the Irish can't drink. What you always have to remember with the Irish is they get mean. Virtually every Irish I've known gets mean when he drinks. Particularly the real Irish.\"<ref>[[Adam Nagourney|Nagourney, Adam]] (2010-12-10) [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/11/us/politics/11nixon.html?_r=2&hp In Tapes, Nixon Rails About Jews and Blacks], ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\nDiscrimination against Irish Americans differed depending on gender. For example, Irish women were sometimes stereotyped as \"reckless breeders\" because some American Protestants feared high Catholic birth rates would eventually result in a Protestant minority. Many native-born Americans claimed that \"their incessant childbearing [would] ensure an Irish political takeover of American cities [and that] Catholicism would become the reigning faith of the hitherto Protestant nation.\"<ref>{{cite book| last=Diner| first=Hasia R.| title=Erin's Daughters| page=62}}</ref> Irish men were also targeted, but in a different way than women were. The difference between the Irish female \"Bridget\" and the Irish male \"Pat\" was distinct; while she was impulsive but fairly harmless, he was \"always drunk, eternally fighting, lazy, and shiftless\". In contrast to the view that Irish women were shiftless, slovenly and stupid (like their male counterparts), girls were said to be \"industrious, willing, cheerful, and honest\u2014they work hard, and they are very strictly moral\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Irish Immigrants in America During the 19th Century| url=http://www.kinsella.org/history/histira.htm| work=The Kinsella Homepage| accessdate=17 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Whelehan| first=Niall| title=The Dynamiters: Irish Nationalism and Political Violence in the Wider World, 1867-1900| year=2012| location=Cambridge| pages=217\u2013245}}</ref>\n\nThere were also [[Darwinian]]-inspired excuses for the discrimination of the Irish in America. Many Americans believed that since the Irish were [[Celts]] and not [[Anglo-Saxons]], they were racially inferior and deserved second-hand citizenship. The Irish being of inferior intelligence was a belief held by many Americans. This notion was held due to the fact that the Irish topped the charts demographically in terms of arrests and imprisonment. They also had more people confined to [[insane asylum]]s and [[poorhouse]]s than any other group. The racial supremacy belief that many Americans had at the time contributed significantly to Irish discrimination.<ref>{{cite book| last=Casey| first=Marion| title=Making the Irish American: History and Heritage of the Irish in the United States| year=2006| publisher=New York University Press| page=367| url=https://books.google.com/?id=c5TPHakJ98cC&printsec=frontcover&dq=making+the+irish+american#v=onepage&q=making%20the%20irish%20american&f=false| isbn=9780814752081}}</ref>\n\n===Contributions to American culture===\n{{details|List of Irish Americans}}\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2011}}\n[[File:StPatrickCathedral small.jpg|thumb|upright|[[St. Patrick's Cathedral, New York]]]]\nThe annual celebration of [[Saint Patrick's Day]] is a widely recognized symbol of the Irish presence in America. The largest celebration of the holiday takes place in New York, where the annual St. Patrick's Day Parade draws an average of two million people. The second-largest celebration is held in Boston. The South Boston Parade is one the nation's oldest, dating back to 1737. [[Savannah, Georgia]], also holds one of the largest parades in the United States.\n\nSince the arrival of nearly two million Irish immigrants in the 1840s, the urban Irish police officer and firefighter have become virtual icons of American popular culture. In many large cities, the police and fire departments have been dominated by the Irish for over 100 years, even after the ethnic Irish residential populations in those cities dwindled to small minorities. Many police and fire departments maintain large and active \"[[Emerald Society|Emerald Societies]]\", bagpipe marching groups, or other similar units demonstrating their members' pride in their Irish heritage.\n\nWhile these archetypal images are especially well known, Irish Americans have contributed to U.S. culture in a wide variety of fields: the fine and performing arts, film, literature, politics, sports, and religion. The Irish-American contribution to popular entertainment is reflected in the careers of figures such as [[James Cagney]], [[Bing Crosby]], [[Walt Disney]], [[John Ford]], [[Judy Garland]],<ref>Flynn, John & Jerry Kelleher. ''Dublin Journeys in America'' pp. 150\u2013153, High Table Publishing, 2003, {{ISBN|0-9544694-1-0}}</ref> [[Gene Kelly]], [[Grace Kelly]], [[Tyrone Power]], [[Chuck Connors]], [[Ada Rehan]], [[Jena Malone]], and [[Spencer Tracy]]. Irish-born actress [[Maureen O'Hara]],<ref>Flynn, John & Jerry Kelleher. ''Dublin Journeys in America'' pp. 148\u2013149, High Table Publishing, 2003, {{ISBN|0-9544694-1-0}}</ref> who became an American citizen, defined for U.S. audiences the archetypal, feisty Irish \"colleen\" in popular films such as ''[[The Quiet Man]]'' and ''[[The Long Gray Line]]''. More recently, the Irish-born [[Pierce Brosnan]] gained screen celebrity as [[James Bond]]. During the early years of television, popular figures with Irish roots included [[Gracie Allen]], [[Art Carney]], [[Joe Flynn (US actor)|Joe Flynn]], [[Jackie Gleason]], [[Luke Gordon]] and [[Ed Sullivan]].\n\nSince the late days of the film industry, celluloid representations of Irish Americans have been plentiful. Famous films with Irish-American themes include social dramas such as ''[[Little Nellie Kelly]]'' and ''[[The Cardinal]]'', labor epics like ''[[On the Waterfront]]'', and gangster movies such as ''[[Angels with Dirty Faces]]'', ''[[The Friends of Eddie Coyle]]'', and ''[[The Departed]]''. Irish-American characters have been featured in popular television series such as ''[[Ryan's Hope]]'', ''[[Rescue Me (U.S. TV series)|Rescue Me]]'' and ''[[Blue Bloods (TV series)|Blue Bloods]]''.\n\nProminent Irish-American literary figures include [[Pulitzer Prize|Pulitzer]] and [[Nobel Prize]]\u2013winning playwright [[Eugene O'Neill]], [[Jazz Age]] novelist [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]], author and poet [[Edgar Allan Poe]],<ref>Arthur Hobson Quinn, 'Edgar Allan Poe: a critical biography' (1997), p. 13</ref> social realist [[James T. Farrell]], and [[Southern Gothic]] writer [[Flannery O'Connor]]. The 19th-century novelist [[Henry James]] was also of partly Irish descent. While Irish Americans have been underrepresented in the plastic arts, two well-known American painters claim Irish roots. 20th-century painter [[Georgia O'Keeffe]] was born to an Irish-American father, and 19th-century [[trompe-l'\u0153il]] painter [[William Harnett]] emigrated from Ireland to the United States.\n\nThe Irish-American contribution to politics spans the entire ideological spectrum. Two prominent American socialists, [[Mary Harris Jones|Mary Harris \"Mother\" Jones]] and [[Elizabeth Gurley Flynn]], were Irish Americans. In the 1960s, Irish-American writer [[Michael Harrington]] became an influential advocate of social welfare programs. Harrington's views profoundly influenced President [[John F. Kennedy]] and his brother, [[Robert F. Kennedy]]. Meanwhile, Irish-American political writer [[William F. Buckley]] emerged as a major intellectual force in [[American conservative]] politics in the latter half of the 20th century. Buckley's magazine, ''[[National Review]]'', proved an effective advocate of successful [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidates such as [[Ronald Reagan]].\n\nNotorious Irish Americans include the legendary New Mexico outlaw [[Billy the Kid]].<ref name=\"wallis6\">Wallis (2007), p. 6.</ref><ref name=\"utley2\">Utley (1989), p. 2.</ref> Many historians believe he was born in New York City to Famine-era immigrants from Ireland.<ref name=\"wallis6\" /><ref name=\"utley2\" /> [[Mary Mallon]], also known as ''Typhoid Mary'', was an Irish immigrant, as was [[Procuring (prostitution)|madam]] [[Josephine Airey]], who also went by the name of \"Chicago Joe\" Hensley. [[New Orleans]] socialite and murderer [[Delphine LaLaurie]], whose maiden name was Macarty, was of partial paternal Irish ancestry. [[Irish Mob|Irish-American mobsters]] include, amongst others, [[Dean O'Banion]], [[Legs Diamond|Jack \"Legs\" Diamond]], [[James McLean (mobster)|Buddy McLean]], [[Howie Winter]] and [[Whitey Bulger]]. [[Lee Harvey Oswald]], the assassin of John F. Kennedy, had an Irish-born great-grandmother by the name of Mary Tonry.<ref>Louisiana census</ref> Colorful Irish Americans also include [[Margaret Brown|Margaret Tobin]] of ''[[RMS Titanic]]'' fame, scandalous model [[Evelyn Nesbit]], dancer [[Isadora Duncan]], [[San Francisco]] madam [[Tessie Wall]], and [[Nellie Cashman]], nurse and gold prospector in the [[American West]].\n\nThe wide popularity of Celtic music has fostered the rise of Irish-American bands that draw heavily on traditional Irish themes and music. Such groups include New York City's [[Black 47]], founded in the late 1980s, blending [[punk rock]], [[rock and roll]], [[Irish music]], rap/[[hip hop music|hip-hop]], [[reggae]], and [[soul music|soul]]; and the [[Dropkick Murphys]], a Celtic punk band formed in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]], nearly a decade later. [[The Decemberists]], a band featuring Irish-American singer [[Colin Meloy]], released \"Shankill Butchers\", a song that deals with the [[Ulster loyalism|Ulster Loyalist]] [[Shankill Butchers|gang of the same name]]. The song appears on their album ''[[The Crane Wife]]''. [[Flogging Molly]], led by Dublin-born [[Dave King (Irish singer)|Dave King]], are relative newcomers building upon this new tradition.\n\n====Sports====\nStarting with the sons of the famine generation, the Irish dominated baseball and boxing, and played a major role in other sports. \n\n[[File:C's banner.JPG|thumb|upright|right|Logo of the [[Boston Celtics]] basketball team]]\nFamous in their day were [[NFL]] quarterbacks and [[Super Bowl]] champions [[John Elway]] and [[Tom Brady]], [[NBA]] forward [[Rick Barry]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nba/lists/Top-10-small-forwards-in-NBA-history#tab=photo-title=Rick+Barry+%25281965-80%2529&photo=30170280|title=Top 10 small forwards in NBA history|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> tennis greats [[Jimmy Connors]] and [[John McEnroe]], baseball pitcher [[Nolan Ryan]], baseball shortstop [[Derek Jeter]], basketball point guard [[Jason Kidd]], boxing legend [[Jack Dempsey]], world champion pro surfer [[Kelly Slater]], national champion skier [[Ryan Max Riley]], and legendary golfer [[Ben Hogan]].\n\n=====Baseball=====\n[[File:Eric Bruntlett 2009.jpg|thumb|upright|left|The [[Philadelphia Phillies]] started the tradition of wearing green uniforms on St. Patrick's day.]]\nThe Irish dominated professional baseball in the late 19th century, making up a third or more of the players and many of the top stars and managers.  The professional teams played in northeastern cities with large Irish populations that provided a fan base, as well as training for ambitious youth.<ref>David L. Fleitz, ''The Irish in Baseball: An Early History'' (2009)</ref> Casway argues that:\n{{quote|Baseball for Irish kids was a shortcut to the American dream and to self-indulgent glory and fortune. By the mid-1880s these young Irish men dominated the sport and popularized a style of play that was termed heady, daring, and spontaneous.... [[Ed Delahanty]] personified the flamboyant, exciting spectator-favorite, the Casey-at-the-bat, Irish slugger. The handsome masculine athlete who is expected to live as large as he played.<ref>Jerrold Casway, '' Ed Delahanty in the Emerald Age of Baseball'' (2004) p. x</ref>}}\n\nIrish stars included [[Charles Comiskey]], [[Connie Mack]], [[King Kelly|Michael \"King\" Kelly]], [[Roger Connor]], [[Eddie Collins]], [[Roger Bresnahan]], [[Ed Walsh]] and New York Giants manager [[John McGraw]]. The large 1945 class of inductees enshrined in the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame]] in Cooperstown included nine Irish Americans.\n\nThe [[Philadelphia Phillies]] always play at home during [[Grapefruit League|spring training]] on St. Patrick's Day. The Phillies hold the distinction of being the first baseball team to wear green uniforms on St. Patricks Day. The tradition was started by Phillies pitcher [[Tug McGraw]], who dyed his uniform green the night before March 17, 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/columnists/paul_hagen/20110318_Paul_Hagen__When_Tug_McGraw_broke_the_color_barrier_with_Phillies.html|title=When Tug McGraw broke the color barrier with Phillies|publisher=Philadelphia Media Network|author=Hagen, Paul|date=2011-03-18|accessdate=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n\n=====Boxing=====\n[[File:SullivanCorbettBubbleMascot.JPG|right|thumb|Two Irish stars: [[James J. Corbett|\"Gentleman Jim\" Corbett]] licks John L. Sullivan in 1892]]\n[[John L. Sullivan]]  (1858\u20131918), The heavyweight boxing champion, was the first of the modern sports superstars, winning scores of contests \u2013 perhaps as many as 200\u2014with a purse that reached the fabulous sum of one million dollars.<ref>Ralph Wilcox, \"Irish Americans in Sports: The Nineteenth Century\" in Joseph J. Lee and Marion R. Casey, eds. ''Making the Irish American: History and heritage of the Irish in the United States'' (2006) pp. 443-55</ref><ref>Michael T. Isenberg, ''John L. Sullivan and His America'' ([[University of Illinois Press]], 1994)</ref>\n\n=====Gaelic sports=====\nThe Irish brought their native games of [[Gaelic handball|handball]], [[hurling]] and [[Gaelic football]] to America. Along with [[camogie]], these sports are part of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]]. The [[North American GAA]] organization is still strong, with 128 clubs across its 10 divisions.<ref>[http://usgaa.org/division/western-division/ \"Divisions & Clubs\"], USGAA</ref>\n\n====Entertainment====\n[[File:Tom Cruise by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|185px|right|Actor [[Tom Cruise]] descends from paternal Irish (\"[[Cruise (name)|Cruise]]\" and \"O'Mara\") lineage around [[County Dublin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/tom-cruise-proud-of-his-irish-ancestry-29172184.html|title=Tom Cruise proud of his Irish ancestry|website=Independent.ie|date=April 3, 2013|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishfamilyhistorycentre.com/article/tom-cruises-irish-ancestry|title=Tom Cruise's Irish Ancestry|website=Irish Family History Centre|date=2013|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>]]\nIrish Americans have been prominent in comedy. Notable comedians of Irish descent include [[Jackie Gleason]], [[George Carlin]], [[Bill Burr]], [[Bill Murray]], [[Will Ferrell]], [[Bryan Callen]], [[Pete Holmes]], [[Joe Rogan]], [[Ben Stiller]], [[Chris Farley]], [[Stephen Colbert]], [[Conan O'Brien]], [[Denis Leary]] (holds dual American and Irish citizenship),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oprah.com/entertainment/Favorite-Irish-Entertainers/2 |title=Our Favorite Irish Imports |publisher=Oprah.com |date=March 16, 2009 |accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref> [[Colin Quinn]], [[Charles Nelson Reilly]], [[Bill Maher]], [[Molly Shannon]], [[John Mulaney]], [[Kathleen Madigan]], [[Jimmy Fallon]], [[Des Bishop]], and [[Jim Gaffigan]], among others. Musicians of Irish descent include [[Christina Aguilera]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Kurt Cobain]], [[Bing Crosby]], [[Tori Kelly]], [[Tim McGraw]], [[Mandy Moore]], [[Hilary Duff]], [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]], [[Judy Garland]], [[Katy Perry]], [[Tom Petty]], [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Britney Spears]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], [[Gwen Stefani]], [[Taylor Swift]], [[Justin Timberlake]], [[Prodigy (rapper)|Prodigy]], [[Post Malone]] and others.\n\nFictional Irish Americans:\nIn the Comic Strips:\n*Maggie and Jiggs of [[Bringing Up Father]]\n*Police Chief Pat Patton of [[Dick Tracy]]\n*Beetle Bailey and his sister Lous {Bailey} Flagston of [[Beetle Bailey]] and [[Hi and Lois]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiandlois.com/comics/march-17-2015/|title=March 17, 2015|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sense of heritage===\n[[File:Southie Mural.JPG|thumb|[[Irish Republican]] mural in [[South Boston]], Massachusetts]]\nMany people of Irish descent retain a sense of their Irish heritage. Article 2 of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] formally recognizes and embraces this fact: <blockquote>\u2026the Irish Nation cherishes its special affinity with people of Irish ancestry living abroad who share its cultural identity and heritage.</blockquote>\n[[File:Chicago River dyed green, focus on river.jpg|thumb|The [[Chicago River]], dyed green for the 2005 [[St. Patrick's Day]] celebration]]\nIrish independence from the United Kingdom encouraged the hope that descendants of Irish abroad who had retained a cultural connection and identified with Ireland would resettle there, as opposed to attracting immigrants from other cultures in other countries. One member of an Irish government of the early republic expressed his hope as follows:\n\n<blockquote>I do not think [the [[Irish Free State]]] will afford sufficient allurements to the citizens of other States ... The children of Irish parents born abroad are sometimes more Irish than the Irish themselves, and they would come with added experience and knowledge to our country....|4=Sen. [[Patrick W. Kenny|Patrick Kenny]], [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]] 1924,&nbsp;<ref name=FisheryBill>{{cite web|first=Patrick |last=Kenny |title=Seanad \u00c9ireann \u2013 Volume 2 \u2013 15 January 1924 |url=http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/S/0002/S.0002.192401150005.html |accessdate=2006-11-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607065150/http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/S/0002/S.0002.192401150005.html |archivedate=7 June 2011 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nA sense of exile, [[Irish diaspora|diaspora]], and (in the case of songs) even nostalgia is a common theme.<ref>Cronin, Michael and Barbara O'Connor. ''Irish Tourism: Image, Culture, and Identity''. [[Clevedon]], UK: Channel View Publications, 2003. (pg. 197-198) {{ISBN|1-873150-54-7}}</ref><ref>Harrington, John P., ed. ''Irish Theater in America: Essays on Irish Theatrical Diaspora''. [[Syracuse, New York]]: Syracuse University Press, 2009. (pg. 40) {{ISBN|0-8156-3169-3}}</ref> The modern term \"[[Plastic Paddy]]\" generally refers to someone who was not born in Ireland and is separated from his closest Irish-born ancestor by several generations but still considers themselves \"Irish\". It is occasionally used in a derogatory fashion towards Irish Americans, in an attempt to undermine the \"Irishness\" of the Irish diaspora based on [[nationality]] and ([[citizenship]]) rather than [[ethnicity]].<ref>{{cite web\n| date = 2006-03-17\n| title = Erin Go ARGH! The case against St. Patrick's Day. (And, no, I'm not British.)\n| author = Alex Massie\n| url = http://www.nationalreview.com/comment/massie200603170817.asp\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web | author = Michelle Byrne | title = Are you a plastic Paddy? | url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/showbiz/article-17050544-are-you-a-plastic-paddy.do | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110605082238/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/showbiz/article-17050544-are-you-a-plastic-paddy.do | archivedate = 2011-06-05 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxingandmma/5496836/Dan-Hardys-UFC-clash-with-Marcus-Davis-set-to-produce-fireworks.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=Dan Hardy's UFC clash with Marcus Davis set to produce fireworks | first=Gareth A. | last=Davies | date=2009-06-10 | accessdate=2010-05-05}}</ref> The term is freely applied to relevant people of all nationalities, not solely Irish Americans.\n\nSome Irish Americans were enthusiastic supporters of Irish independence; the [[Fenian Brotherhood]] movement was based in the United States and in the late 1860s launched several unsuccessful attacks on British-controlled Canada known as the \"[[Fenian Raids]]\".<ref>Senior, Hereward. ''The Last Invasion of Canada: The Fenian Raids, 1866\u20131870''. Toronto and Oxford: Dundurn Press, 1991. {{ISBN|1550020854}}</ref> The [[Provisional IRA]] received significant funding and volunteers for its paramilitary activities from Irish expatriates and Irish American supporters\u2014in 1984, the [[United States Department of Justice|US Department of Justice]] won a court case forcing the Irish American fund-raising organization [[NORAID]] to acknowledge the Provisional IRA as its \"foreign principal\".<ref name=\"CAIN\">{{cite web| first= Andrew J. | last=Wilson | url = http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/events/aia/wilson95.htm | title = The Congressional Friends of Ireland and the Anglo-Irish Agreement, 1981\u20131985 | publisher = Conflict Archive on the Internet (CAIN) | accessdate = 2008-04-14}}</ref>\n\n====Cities====\n{{Main|History of the Irish in Baltimore|History of the Irish in Boston|History of the Irish in Indianapolis|History of the Irish in Louisville|History of the Irish in Saint Paul|History of the Irish in New York City|Irish Americans in New York City|History of the Irish Americans in Philadelphia}}\n\n[[File:Irish American2.png|thumb|Population density of people born in Ireland, 1870; these were mostly Catholics; the older Scots Irish immigration is not shown.]]\nThe vast majority of Irish Catholic Americans settled in large and small cities across the North, particularly railroad centers and mill towns. They became perhaps the most urbanized group in America, as few became farmers.<ref>Kenny (2000) p. 105\u20136</ref> Areas that retain a significant Irish American population include the metropolitan areas of [[Boston]], [[New York City]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], [[Pittsburgh]], [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[Baltimore]], [[St. Louis]], [[Chicago]], [[Cleveland]], [[San Francisco]], Savannah, and [[Los Angeles]], where most new arrivals of the 1830\u20131910 period settled. As a percentage of the population, Massachusetts is the most Irish state, with about a fifth, 21.2%,  of the population claiming Irish descent.<ref>{{cite web|author=United States Census Bureau |authorlink=United States Census Bureau |title=Irish-American Heritage Month (March) and St. Patrick's Day (March 17): 2009 |url=https://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/facts_for_features_special_editions/013130.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302162055/http://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/facts_for_features_special_editions/013130.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 2 March 2009 |work=Facts for Features & Special Editions |publisher=US Census Bureau Press Releases |date=2009-01-05 |accessdate=1 July 2009 }}</ref> The most Irish American towns in the United States are [[Scituate, Massachusetts]], with 47.5% of its residents being of Irish descent; [[Milton, Massachusetts]], with 44.6% of its 26,000 being of Irish descent; and [[Braintree, Massachusetts]] with 46.5% of its 34,000 being of Irish descent. ([[Weymouth, Massachusetts]], at 39% of its 54,000 citizens, and [[Quincy, Massachusetts]], at 34% of its population of 90,000, are the two most Irish ''cities'' in the country. [[Squantum (Quincy, Massachusetts)|Squantum]], a peninsula in the northern part of Quincy, is the most Irish neighborhood in the country, with close to 60% of its 2600 residents claiming Irish descent.)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stonehill.edu/x23231.xml |title=The Most Irish Town in America is Named |author=Muldoon, Molly |date=January 10, 2011 |publisher=IrishCentral.com |accessdate=October 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523041617/http://www.stonehill.edu/x23231.xml |archivedate=May 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nPhiladelphia, Boston, New York, and Chicago have historically had neighborhoods with higher percentages of Irish American residents. Regionally, the most Irish American states are Massachusetts, [[New Hampshire]], [[Maine]], [[Vermont]], [[Rhode Island]], [[Delaware]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[Connecticut]], according to the U.S. Census Bureau American Community Survey in 2013.<ref name=\"2013 ACS\">{{cite web| url = http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/13_1YR/DP02 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20200212093727/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/13_1YR/DP02 | url-status = dead | archive-date = February 12, 2020 | title = Selected Social Characteristics in the United States (DP02): 2013 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates| publisher = U.S. Census Bureau | accessdate = December 11, 2014}}</ref> In consequence of its unique history as a mining center, [[Butte, Montana]], is also one of the country's most thoroughly Irish American cities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.butteamerica.com/birish.htm |title=Butte, Montana: Ireland's Fifth Province |author=Everett, George |year=2008 |website= |publisher=ButteAmerica.com |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref> Smaller towns, such as [[Greeley, Nebraska]] (population 466), with an estimated 51.7% of the residents identifying as Irish American as of 2009\u201313<ref>{{cite web| url = http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/13_5YR/DP02/1600000US3120050 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20200212084542/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/13_5YR/DP02/1600000US3120050 | url-status = dead | archive-date = February 12, 2020 | title = Selected Social Characteristics in the United States (DP02): 2013 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates: Greeley Center village, Nebraska| publisher = U.S. Census Bureau | accessdate = December 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theirishgazette.com/index.php/category-table/98-greeley-nebraska-hosts-4th-irish-festival- |title=Greeley Nebraska Hosts 4th Irish Festival |author=Brooks, Jim |date=September 16, 2010 |website= |publisher=TheIrishGazette.com |accessdate=October 22, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> were part of the Irish Catholic Colonization effort of Bishop O'Connor of New York in the 1880s.<ref>Moloney, Deirdre M. ''American Catholic Lay Groups and Transatlantic Social Reform in the Progressive Era''. Chapel Hill, North Carolina: University of North Carolina Press, 2002. (pg. 86) {{ISBN|0-8078-4986-3}}</ref>\n\nThe states with the top percentages of Irish:\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* {{flagicon|Massachusetts}} [[Massachusetts]] (22.5%)\n* {{flagicon|New Hampshire}} [[New Hampshire]] (20.5%)\n* {{flagicon|Rhode Island}} [[Rhode Island]] (18.4%)\n* {{flagicon|Maine}} [[Maine]] (18.0%)\n* {{flagicon|Vermont}} [[Vermont]] (18.0%)\n* {{flagicon|Delaware}} [[Delaware]] (16.7%)\n* {{flagicon|Pennsylvania}} [[Pennsylvania]] (16.6%)\n* {{flagicon|Connecticut}} [[Connecticut]] (16.6%)\n* {{flagicon|New Jersey}} [[New Jersey]] (15.9%)\n* {{flagicon|West Virginia}} [[West Virginia]] (14.8%)\n* {{flagicon|Montana}} [[Montana]] (14.8%)\n* {{flagicon|Iowa}} [[Iowa]] (13.6%)\n* {{flagicon|Ohio}} [[Ohio]] (13.5%)\n* {{flagicon|Nebraska}} [[Nebraska]] (13.4%)\n* {{flagicon|Wyoming}} [[Wyoming]] (13.3%)\n* {{flagicon|Missouri}} [[Missouri]] (13.2%)\n* {{flagicon|New York}} [[New York (state)|New York]] (12.9%)\n* {{flagicon|Kansas}} [[Kansas]] (12.4%)\n* {{flagicon|Illinois}} [[Illinois]] (12.2%)\n* {{flagicon|Colorado}} [[Colorado]] (12.2%)\n* {{flagicon|Kentucky}} [[Kentucky]] (12.2%)\n* {{flagicon|Oregon}} [[Oregon]] (12.1%)\n* {{flagicon|Maryland}} [[Maryland]] (11.7%)\n* {{flagicon|Indiana}} [[Indiana]] (11.6%)\n* {{flagicon|Oklahoma}} [[Oklahoma]] (11.5%)\n* {{flagicon|Washington}} [[Washington (state)|Washington]] (11.4%)\n* {{flagicon|Minnesota}} [[Minnesota]] (11.2%)\n* {{flagicon|Michigan}} [[Michigan]] (11.0%)\n* {{flagicon|Wisconsin}} [[Wisconsin]] (11.0%)\n* {{flagicon|Nevada}} [[Nevada]] (10.9%)\n* {{flagicon|Alaska}} [[Alaska]] (10.8%)\n* {{flagicon|Arkansas}} [[Arkansas]] (10.7%)\n* {{flagicon|Tennessee}} [[Tennessee]] (10.6%)\n* {{flagicon|South Dakota}} [[South Dakota]] (10.4%)\n* {{flagicon|Florida}} [[Florida]] (10.3%)\n* {{flagicon|Arizona}} [[Arizona]] (10.2%)\n* {{flagicon|Idaho}} [[Idaho]] (10.0%)\n* {{flagicon|Virginia}} [[Virginia]] (9.8%)\n* {{flagicon|South Carolina}} [[South Carolina]] (8.8%)\n* {{flagicon|Georgia (U.S. state)}} [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] (7.9%)\n* {{flagicon|Alabama}} [[Alabama]] (7.8%)\n* {{flagicon|California}} [[California]] (7.7%)\n* {{flagicon|North Dakota}} [[North Dakota]] (7.7%)\n* {{flagicon|North Carolina}} [[North Carolina]] (7.5%)\n* {{flagicon|Texas}} [[Texas]] (7.2%)\n* {{flagicon|Louisiana}} [[Louisiana]] (7.0%)\n* {{flagicon|Mississippi}} [[Mississippi]] (6.9%)\n* {{flagicon|Utah}} [[Utah]] (5.9%)\n* {{flagicon|District of Columbia}} [[District of Columbia]] (5.5%)\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Irish-American communities====\n{{Main|List of Irish-American communities}}\nAccording to the 2010 U.S. Census, the city of [[Butte, Montana]] has the highest percentage of Irish Americans [[per capita]] of any city in the United States, with around one-quarter of the population reporting Irish ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 12, 2017|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/la-tr-montana-irish-meagher-20170312-htmlstory.html|title=Celebrate St. Patrick's Day in the most Irish place in the U.S.--and we're not talking about Boston|accessdate=October 30, 2017|author=Pockock, Joanna}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Irish Central|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/news/butte-montana-is-the-most-irish-american-city-according-to-2010-us-census-167528645-237525161|title=Butte, Montana is the most Irish American city according to 2010 US census|author=O'Shea, Kerry|date=August 27, 2012|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> Butte's Irish Catholic population originated with the waves of Irish immigrants who arrived in the city in the late-nineteenth century to work in the industrial [[mining|mines]]. By population, however, [[List of U.S. cities with large Irish-American populations|Boston and Philadelphia]] have the two largest Irish American populations in the country. There are Irish neighborhoods scattered all throughout Boston, most notably [[South Boston]]. Many of Philadelphia's Irish neighborhoods are located in the [[Northeast Philadelphia]] section of the city, particularly in the [[Fishtown, Philadelphia|Fishtown]], [[Mayfair, Philadelphia|Mayfair]], and [[Kensington, Philadelphia|Kensington]] neighborhoods, as well as the [[South Philadelphia]] section, most notably the [[Pennsport, Philadelphia|Pennsport]] (\"Two Street\" to the locals)  neighborhood. There are large Irish populations in the [[Greater Boston|Boston]] and [[Delaware Valley|Philadelphia]] metropolitan areas as well. The [[South Side, Chicago|South Side]] of [[Chicago, Illinois]] also has a large Irish community, who refer to themselves as the [[Southside Irish]].\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main list|List of Irish Americans}}\n\n===In politics and government===\n[[File:AlfredSmith.jpg|thumb|left|upright=.85|[[1928 United States presidential election|1928 Democratic Presidential Nominee]] [[Al Smith]] was the first [[Irish Catholics|Irish Catholic]] nominee of a major political party.]]\n\nThe [[United States Declaration of Independence]] contained 56 delegate signatures. Of the signers, eight were of Irish descent. Three signers, [[Matthew Thornton]], [[George Taylor (Pennsylvania politician)|George Taylor]] and [[James Smith (Pennsylvania politician)|James Smith]], were born in Ireland; the remaining five Irish Americans, [[George Read (American politician, born 1733)|George Read]], [[Thomas McKean]], [[Thomas Lynch Jr.]], [[Edward Rutledge]], and [[Charles Carroll of Carrollton|Charles Carroll]], were the sons or grandsons of Irish immigrants. Though not a delegate but the secretary at the Congress, [[Charles Thomson]], also Irish American, signed as well. The [[United States Constitution]] was created by [[Constitutional Convention (United States)|a convention]] of 36 delegates. Of these, at least six were of Irish ancestry. George Read and Thomas McKean had already worked on the Declaration, and were joined by [[John Rutledge]], [[William Paterson (judge)|William Paterson]], [[Pierce Butler]], [[Daniel Carroll]], and [[Thomas Fitzsimons]]. The Carrolls and Fitzsimons were [[Irish Catholics|Catholic]], the remainder [[Scotch-Irish Americans|Protestant]].<ref name=\"Glazier 1999 p. 185\">{{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Joseph F. X.|editor-last=Glazier|editor-first=Michael|title=The Encyclopedia of the Irish in America|year=1999|chapter=The Constitution of the United States|place=[[Notre Dame, Indiana|Notre Dame, IN]]|publisher=University of Notre Dame Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse/page/185 185]|isbn=978-0268027551|quote=[Thomas Fitzsimons] was one of the two Catholic delegates to the Convention (Daniel Carroll was the other).|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse/page/185}}</ref><ref name=\"Glazier 1999 p. 205\">{{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Joseph F. X.|editor-last=Glazier|editor-first=Michael|title=The Encyclopedia of the Irish in America|year=1999|chapter=The Declaration of Independence|place=[[Notre Dame, Indiana|Notre Dame, IN]]|publisher=University of Notre Dame Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse/page/205 205]|isbn=978-0268027551|quote=Another late signer was Charles Carroll of Carrollton (1737\u20131832), the only Roman Catholic signer.|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofir0000unse/page/205}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1850s, the Irish were already a major presence in the police departments of large cities. In New York City in 1855, of the city's 1,149 policemen, 305 were natives of Ireland. Within 30 years, Irish Americans in the NYPD were almost twice their proportion of the city's population.<ref name=\"Watkin\"/> Both Boston's police and fire departments provided many Irish immigrants with their first jobs. The creation of a unified police force in Philadelphia opened the door to the Irish in that city. By 1860 in Chicago, 49 of the 107 on the police force were Irish. Chief O'Leary headed the police force in New Orleans, and Malachi Fallon was chief of police of San Francisco.<ref name=\"potter530\">Potter (1960), p. 530</ref>\n\nThe Irish Catholic diaspora are very well-organized{{clarify|date=January 2017}} and since 1850 have produced a majority of the leaders of the U.S. Catholic Church, labor unions, the Democratic Party in larger cities, and Catholic high schools, colleges and universities.<ref>Helmreich, William B. ''The Things They Say Behind Your Back: Stereotypes and the Myths Behind Them''. 5th ed. [[Piscataway, New Jersey]]: Transaction Publishers, 1984. (pg. 158) {{ISBN|0-87855-953-1}}</ref>\n\nMany major cities have elected Irish American Catholic mayors. Indeed, [[Boston]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Baltimore]], [[Cincinnati]], [[Houston]], [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New York City]], [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]], [[Scranton, Pennsylvania|Scranton]], [[Pittsburgh]], [[St. Louis]], [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], and [[San Francisco]] have all elected natives of Ireland as mayors. [[Chicago]], Boston, and [[Jersey City, New Jersey]] have had more Irish American mayors than any other ethnic group.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}} The cities of [[Milwaukee]] {{small|([[Tom Barrett (Wisconsin politician)|Tom Barrett]]; 2004-)}} and [[Detroit]] {{small|([[Mike Duggan]]; 2012-)}} currently ({{As of|2018|lc=on}}) have Irish American mayors. Pittsburgh mayor [[Bob O'Connor (mayor)|Bob O'Connor]] died in office in 2006. New York City has had at least three Irish-born mayors and over eight Irish American mayors. The most recent one was [[County Mayo]] native [[William O'Dwyer]], elected in 1949.<ref>Moreno, Barry. ''Images of America: Ellis Island's Famous Immigrants''. Arcadia Publishing, 2008. (pg. 47) {{ISBN|0-7385-5533-9}}</ref><ref>William B. Prendergast, ''The Catholic Voter in American Politics: The Passing of the Democratic Monolith'' (1999)</ref>\n\nThe Irish Protestant vote has not been studied nearly as much. Historian Timothy J. Meagher argues that by the late 19th century, most of the Protestant Irish \"turned their backs on all associations with Ireland and melted into the American Protestant mainstream.\" A minority insisted on a \"Scotch-Irish\" identity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Timothy J. Meagher|title=The Columbia Guide to Irish American History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=miEAjSOA1fAC&pg=PA92|year=2013|page=92|isbn=9780231510707}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, by contrast, Irish Protestants remained a political force, with many belonging to the [[Orange Order]].<ref>James R. Miller, \"Anti-Catholic Thought in Victorian Canada,\" ''Canadian Historical Review'' (1985) 66#4 pp 474-494.</ref> It was an anti-Catholic social organization with chapters across Canada. It was most powerful during the late 19th century.<ref>Stephen Kenny, \"A Prejudice that Rarely Utters Its Name: A Historiographical and Historical Reflection upon North American Anti-Catholicism,\" ''American Review of Canadian Studies'' (2002) 32#4 pp 639-672</ref><ref>See Hereward Senior \"Orange Order\" in ''Canadian Encyclopedia'' (2015).</ref>\n\n=== Political leanings ===\n{{Further|Catholic Church and politics in the United States}}\n\n[[Al Smith]] and later [[John F. Kennedy]] were the political heroes for Catholics.<ref>Shannon, William V. ''The American Irish: A Political and Social Portrait''. 2nd ed. Boston: University of Massachusetts Press, 1963. (pg. 411) {{ISBN|0-87023-689-X}}</ref> Al Smith, who had an Irish mother and an English-German father, in 1928 became the first Catholic to run for president.<ref>Edmund A. Moore, ''A Catholic Runs for President: The Campaign of 1928'' (1956).</ref> From the 1830s to the 1960s, Irish Catholics voted heavily [[History of the United States Democratic Party|Democratic]], with occasional exceptions like the [[election of 1920]]. Their precincts showed average support levels of 80%.<ref>Paul Kleppner, ''The Third Electoral System 1853-1892'' (1979) p. 182</ref> As historian Lawrence McCaffrey notes, \"until recently they have been so closely associated with the Democratic party that Irish, Catholic, and Democrat composed a trinity of associations, serving mutual interests and needs. \"<ref>{{cite book|author=Lawrence McCaffrey|title=The Irish Catholic Diaspora in America|url=https://archive.org/details/irishcatholicdia00mcca|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=CUA Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/irishcatholicdia00mcca/page/120 120]|isbn=9780813208961}}</ref>\n\nThe great majority of Irish Catholic politicians were Democrats, with a few exceptions before 1970 such as Wisconsin Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]].<ref name=\"Michael Glazier 1999\"/> Today, Irish politicians are associated with both parties. [[Ronald Reagan]] boasted of his Irishness. Historically, Irish Catholics controlled prominent Democratic city organizations.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael C. LeMay|title=Guarding the Gates: Immigration and National Security|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5H0HEOAjDD4C&pg=PA49|year=2006|page=49|isbn=9780275992941}}</ref> Among the most prominent were  New York, Philadelphia, Chicago, Boston, San Francisco, Pittsburgh, Jersey City, and Albany.<ref>These eight are studied in depth in Steven P. Erie, ''Rainbow's End: Irish-Americans and the Dilemmas of Urban Machine Politics, 1840-1985'' (1988).</ref> Many served as chairmen of the Democratic National Committee, including [[County Monaghan]] native [[Thomas Taggart]], Vance McCormick, [[James Farley]], [[Edward J. Flynn]], [[Robert E. Hannegan]], [[J. Howard McGrath]], William H. Boyle, Jr., [[John Moran Bailey]], [[Larry O'Brien]], [[Christopher J. Dodd]], [[Terry McAuliffe]] and [[Tim Kaine]]. In Congress, the Irish are represented in both parties; currently, [[Susan Collins]] of Maine, [[Pat Toomey]] of Pennsylvania, [[Bob Casey, Jr.]] of Pennsylvania, [[Ed Markey]] of Massachusetts, [[Dan Sullivan (U.S. senator)|Dan Sullivan]] of Alaska, [[Lisa Murkowski]] of Alaska, [[Dick Durbin]] of Illinois, [[Patrick Leahy]] of Vermont, and [[Maria Cantwell]] of Washington are Irish Americans serving in the United States Senate. Former Speaker of the House of Representatives and Vice Presidential Candidate [[Paul Ryan]] is another prominent Irish-American Republican. Exit polls show that in recent presidential elections Irish Catholics have split about 50\u201350 for Democratic and Republican candidates.<ref name=\"marlin\">Marlin (2004), pp. 296\u2013345</ref> The [[pro-life]] faction in the Democratic party includes many Irish Catholic politicians, such as the former Boston mayor and ambassador to the Vatican [[Ray Flynn]] and senator [[Bob Casey, Jr.]], who defeated Senator [[Rick Santorum]] in a high visibility race in Pennsylvania in 2006.<ref name=\"prendergast\">Prendergast (1999), p. 1.</ref>\n\n[[File:Irish1346.gif|thumb|left|[[Maps of American ancestries|Distribution]] of Irish Americans according to the 2000 Census]]\nOn one hand, in some areas such as [[New Fairfield, Connecticut|New Fairfield]] and [[Long Island]]. In New York State where [[fusion voting]] is practiced, Irish Americans were instrumental in the founding of the [[Conservative Party of New York State]] in opposition to [[Nelson Rockefeller]] and other liberal Republicans who dominated the state GOP during the 1960s and 70s. On the other, in Massachusetts and elsewhere in Southern New England, significant majorities of the local Irish stayed with the Democratic party.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Timothy J. |last1=Meagher |chapter=The Fireman on the Stairs: Communal Loyalty  |editor-first1=Marion R. |editor-last1=Casey |editor-first2=J. J. |editor-last2=Lee |editorlink2=John Joseph Lee |title=Making the Irish American: History and Heritage of the Irish in the United States |date=2007 |isbn=9780814752180 |page=632|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=cAcUCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA609}}</ref> In some heavily Irish small towns in Northern New England the Irish vote is quite Republican, but other places like Gloucester, New Jersey and Butte, Montana which retain strongly liberal and Democratic leaning Irish populations.\n\nThe voting intentions of Irish Americans and other white ethnic groups attracted attention in the 2016 US election. In the Democratic primaries, Boston's Irish were said to break strongly for [[Hillary Clinton]], whose victories in Irish-heavy Boston suburbs may have helped her narrowly carry the state over [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/us/us-election-did-the-irish-swing-massachusetts-for-hillary-clinton-1.2568212|title=US election: Did the Irish swing Massachusetts for Hillary Clinton|last=Carswell|first=Simon|date=10 March 2016|newspaper=The Irish Times|accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref> A 2016 March survey by Irish Central <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishcentral.com/opinion/in-a-poll-of-irish-readers-donald-trump-has-the-edge-on-hillary-clinton|title=In a poll of Irish readers, Donald Trump has the edge on Hillary Clinton|last=Egan|first=Casey|date=17 March 2016|publisher=Irish Central|accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref> showed that 45% of Irish Americans nationwide supported Trump, although the majority of those in Massachusetts supported Hillary Clinton. An October poll by Buzzfeed showed that Irish respondents nationwide split nearly evenly between Trump (40%) and Clinton (39%), with large numbers either undecided or supporting other candidates (21%), and that the Irish were more supportive of Clinton than all the other West European-descended Americans including fellow Catholic [[Italian Americans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/peteraldhous/trump-and-the-white-vote|title=Which White People Support Trump?|last=Aldhous|first=Peter |author2=Singer-Vine, Jeremy|date=9 October 2017|publisher=Buzzfeed|accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref> In early November 2016, six days before the election, another poll by IrishCentral showed Clinton ahead at 52% among Irish Americans, while Trump was at 40% and the third party candidates together had 8%; Irish respondents in Massachusetts similarly favored Clinton by majority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishcentral.com/news/politics/clinton-polling-high-with-irish-americans-as-election-2016-approaches|title=Clinton would win Irish American vote in 2016 election, our poll results show|date=2 November 2016|publisher=Irish Central|accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref> In the official 2016 election results, Irish-heavy Boston suburbs including on the South Shore witnessed swings to the left (Scituate: +19.5% D, Cohasset: +32.8% D, Milton: +26.6% D, etc.) even as the country as a whole moved right.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} This caused many of the most heavily Irish-descended communities in the country, such as [[Scituate, Massachusetts|Scituate]], to flip from split or Republican-voting to Democrat-voting by significant margins (Scituate: +18% D, Hull: +21% D, Cohasset: +24% D, Milton: +41% D).{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} Despite voting against Trump, many of these same communities had some of the highest levels of opposition to the legalization of marijuana, a typically [[Social conservatism|socially conservative]] position.\n\nIn 2017, a survey with 3,181 Irish American respondents (slightly over half being beyond 3rd generation) by Irish Times found that 41% identified as Democrats while 23% identified as Republicans, while 45% used [[NBC]] (typically considered left-leaning) for their news while 36% used [[Fox News]] (considered right-leaning).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/abroad/how-irish-america-thinks-votes-and-acts-1.3104336|title=How Irish America thinks, votes and acts|author=Liam Kennedy|date=3 June 2017|agency=The Irish Times|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of supporters of Trump among Irish and other [[white ethnic]] communities which had once themselves been marginalized immigrants generated controversy, with [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] Irish American media figures admonishing their co-ethnics against \"myopia\" and \"amnesia\".<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Boston Irish Reporter |title=Historical Myopia: As a majority of Irish Americans reportedly embrace Trump, lessons hard-learned by our immigrant ancestors are evaporating |date=September 6, 2016 |url=http://www.bostonirish.com/history/historical-myopia-majority-irish-americans-reportedly-embrace-trump-lessons-hard-l}}</ref> However, such criticisms by left leaning pundits were frequently leveled against Irish-American conservatives prior to Trump's presidential run, with one columnist from the [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] online magazine [[Salon (website)|Salon]] calling Irish-American conservatives \"disgusting\" in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |magazine=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |title=How did my fellow Irish-Americans get so disgusting |date=March 15, 2014 |url=https://www.salon.com/2014/03/15/how_did_irish_americans_get_so_disgusting/}}</ref> In [[New York City]], the rise of the [[woke]] [[Left wing politics|left]] in the Democratic Party, in addition to the ongoing trends of [[suburbanization]], [[gentrification]], the rise of [[hipster (contemporary subculture)|hipster]] culture, and the increased tendency of Irish-Americans to vote Republican has led to the collapse of Irish political power in the city during the 2010s.<ref>{{cite news |website=cityandstateny.com |title=An Irish lament; the fading of Hibernian political power; 2018 swept away the last bastions of Irish-American influence in NYC politics |date=March 14, 2019 |url=https://www.cityandstateny.com/articles/politics/new-york-state/fading-irish-political-power.html}}</ref> This trend was exemplified by the defeat of [[Queens]] Representative and former [[Democratic Caucus Chairman of the United States House of Representatives|House Democratic Caucus Chairman]] [[Joe Crowley]] by [[Democratic Socialists of America|democratic socialist]] [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] in June 2018.<ref>{{cite news |website=[[Politico]] |title=From future speaker to primary loser: Inside Crowley's crushing defeat |date=June 27, 2018 |url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2018/06/27/from-future-speaker-to-primary-loser-inside-crowleys-crushing-defeat-490979}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |website=[[Irish Times]] |title=Socialist defeats leading Democrat Joe Crowley in New York primary: Victory for newcomer Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez suggests waning power of Irish-American Democrat vote |date=June 27, 2018 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/us/socialist-defeats-leading-democrat-joe-crowley-in-new-york-primary-election-1.3545399}}</ref>  \n\n====American presidents with Irish ancestry====\n[[File:President's Trip to Europe- Motorcade in Dublin. President Kennedy, motorcade, spectators. Dublin, Ireland - NARA - 194227.jpg|thumb|President [[John F. Kennedy]] in motorcade in [[Cork (city)|Cork]] on June 27, 1963]]\n[[File:President Reagan in Ballyporeen Ireland.jpg|thumb|President [[Ronald Reagan]] speaking to a large crowd in his ancestral home in [[Ballyporeen]], Ireland, in 1984.]]\n[[File:Barack Obama shakes hands in Moneygall.jpg|thumb|President Barack Obama greets local residents on Main Street in Moneygall, Ireland, May 23, 2011.]]\nA number of the presidents of the United States have Irish origins.<ref name=\"irishpresidents\">{{cite web|url=http://irishamericanheritage.com/ProcWebPages/1995.htm |title=Irish-American History Month, 1995 |publisher=irishamericanheritage.com |accessdate=2008-04-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509054147/http://irishamericanheritage.com/ProcWebPages/1995.htm |archivedate=2008-05-09 }}</ref> The extent of Irish heritage varies. For example, [[Chester Arthur]]'s father and both of [[Andrew Jackson]]'s parents were Irish-born, while [[George W. Bush]] has a rather distant Irish ancestry. [[Ronald Reagan]]'s father was of Irish ancestry,<ref>{{Cite news| date = September 6, 1981 | author = William Borders | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1981/09/06/world/village-in-tipperary-is-cashing-in-on-ronald-reagan-s-roots.html?sec=travel <!-- old url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=travel&res=980CE7DE103BF935A3575AC0A967948260 --> | title = Village in Tipperary is Cashing In on Ronald Reagan's Roots | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref> while his mother also had some Irish ancestors. [[John F. Kennedy]] had Irish lineage on both sides. Within this group, only Kennedy was raised as a practicing Roman Catholic. [[Barack Obama]]'s Irish heritage originates from his [[Kansas]]-born mother, [[Ann Dunham]], whose ancestry is Irish and English.<ref name=\"The Presidents, Barack Obama\">{{cite web|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/people/presidents/ |title=The Presidents, Barack Obama |publisher=American Heritage.com |accessdate=2009-11-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060210002715/http://www.americanheritage.com/people/presidents/ |archivedate=2006-02-10 }}</ref>\n\n;[[John F. Kennedy]]\n:35th President 1961\u201363 ([[Limerick]] and [[County Wexford]]) First Catholic president, Irish Catholic\n;[[Ronald Reagan]]\n:40th President 1981\u201389: He was the great-grandson, on his father's side, of Irish migrants from [[Ballyporeen|County Tipperary]] who came to America via Canada and England in the 1840s. His mother was of Scottish and English ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/people/presidents/ |title=The Presidents, Ronald Reagan |publisher=American Heritage.com |accessdate=19 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060210002715/http://www.americanheritage.com/people/presidents/ |archivedate=10 February 2006}}</ref>\n;[[George H. W. Bush]]\n:41st President 1989\u201393 ([[County Wexford]]): historians have found that his now apparent ancestor, [[Richard de Clare, 2nd Earl of Pembroke|Richard de Clare, Earl of Pembroke]], shunned by [[Henry II of England|Henry II]], offered his services as a mercenary in the 12th-century Norman invasion of Wexford in exchange for power and land. Strongbow married [[Aoife MacMurrough|Aoife]], daughter of [[Dermot MacMurrough]], the Gaelic [[king of Leinster]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/jan/27/usa.angeliquechrisafis| title=Scion of traitors and warlords: why Bush is coy about his Irish links |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |location=London |first=Angelique |last=Chrisafis |date=2005-01-27}}</ref><ref name=\"DIG\">{{cite web |url=http://homepage.eircom.net/%257Eseanjmurphy/dir/pres.htm |title=American Presidents with Irish Ancestors |publisher=Directory of Irish Genealogy |accessdate=15 April 2008}}</ref>\n;[[George W. Bush]]\n:43rd President 2001\u201309: One of his five times great-grandfathers, William Holliday (a British merchant living in Ireland), was born in Rathfriland, [[County Down]], about 1755 and died in [[Kentucky]] about 1811\u201312. One of the President's seven times great-grandfathers, William Shannon, was  born somewhere in [[County Cork]] about 1730, and died in Pennsylvania in 1784.<ref name=\"DIG\"/>\n;[[Barack Obama]]\n:44th President 2009\u20132017: Some of his maternal ancestors came to America from a small village called [[Moneygall]], in [[County Offaly]].<ref name=\"The Presidents, Barack Obama\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wargs.com/political/obama.html |title=Ancestry of Barack Obama |publisher=William Addams Reitwiesner |accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Irish village of Moneygall gets ready for Barack Obama's visit |author=Henry McDonald |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/25/barack-obama-irish-visit-relatives |date=March 25, 2011 |accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref> His ancestors lived in New England and the South and, by the 1800s, most were in the Midwest.\n\n=====Vice Presidents of Irish descent=====\n;[[Joe Biden]]\n:47th Vice President 2009\u20132017<ref>[http://www.irishabroad.com/news/irish-voice/news/Articles/biden-irish-roots280808.aspx Joe biden's ancestry; interview in 2008], accessed August 2010</ref>\n;[[Mike Pence]]\n:48th Vice President 2017\u2013present\n\n====Irish-American Justices of the Supreme Court====\n:* [[Joseph McKenna]]\n:* [[Edward Douglass White, Jr.|Edward D. White]]\n:* [[Pierce Butler (justice)|Pierce Butler]]\n:* [[Frank Murphy]]\n:* [[James Francis Byrnes]]\n:* [[William J. Brennan]]\n:* [[Anthony Kennedy]]\n:* [[Neil Gorsuch]] Partial maternal Irish ancestry\n:* [[Brett Kavanaugh]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|United States|Ireland}}\n* [[69th Infantry Regiment (New York)]]\n* [[Ethnocultural politics in the United States]]\n* [[Irish American Athletic Club]]\n* [[Irish American Cultural Institute]]\n* [[Irish-American Heritage Month]]\n* [[Irish Brigade (U.S.)]]\n* [[Irish Mob]], criminals in large cities\n* [[Irish Race Conventions]], 19th-century international conventions\n* [[Irish Whales]], athletes\n* [[List of Americans of Irish descent]], notable individuals\n* [[List of Irish-American Medal of Honor recipients]]\n* [[Saint Patrick's Battalion]], [[Mexican\u2013American War]]\n* [[List of Irish-American Medal of Honor recipients]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Over-quotation|both=y|date=January 2020}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n; Bundled references\n{{reflist|group=list}}\n\n==Other sources==\n*Corrigan, Michael, ''Confessions of a Shanty Irishman'', 2014, Virtual Bookworm, eBook and audio book. {{ISBN|978-1602642973}}\n\n==Further reading==\n===References===\n* {{cite book |author=Barkan, Elliott Robert, ed. |title=Making it in America: A Sourcebook on Eminent Ethnic Americans |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WwwY_eJnodgC&pg=PR35 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2001 |isbn=9781576070987}}\n* Byrne, James Patrick, Philip Coleman, and Jason Francis King, eds. ''Ireland and the Americas: culture, politics, and history: a multidisciplinary encyclopedia'' (3 vol. ABC-CLIO, 2008)\n* Glazier, Michael, ed. (1999). ''The Encyclopedia of the Irish in America''. Notre Dame, Indiana: [[University of Notre Dame Press]]. {{ISBN|0-268-02755-2}}\n* Rapple, Brendan A., and Jane Stewart Cook. \"Irish Americans.\" in ''Gale Encyclopedia of Multicultural America'', edited by Thomas Riggs, (3rd ed., vol. 2, Gale, 2014), pp. 459\u2013475. [https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/CX3273300097/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=e2bc8423 Online free]\n\n===General surveys===\n* Anbinder, Tyler, Cormac \u00d3 Gr\u00e1da, Simone A. Wegge, \"[[doi:10.1093/ahr/rhz1023|Networks and Opportunities: A Digital History of Ireland\u2019s Great Famine Refugees in New York]],\" ''The American Historical Review'', Volume 124, Issue 5, December 2019, Pages 1591\u20131629\n*Burchell, Robert A. \"The historiography of the American Irish.\" ''Immigrants & Minorities'' 1.3 (1982): 281\u2013305.  [[doi:10.1080/02619288.1982.9974529|The historiography of the American Irish]]\n* Fanning, Charles (1990/2000). ''The Irish Voice in America: 250 Years of Irish-American Fiction''. Lexington: The University of Kentucky Press. {{ISBN|0-8131-0970-1}}\n* Glynn, Irial: [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:0159-20110201190 Emigration Across the Atlantic: Irish, Italians and Swedes compared, 1800\u20131950], [[European History Online]], Mainz: [[Institute of European History]], 2011, retrieved: June 16, 2011.\n* Jenkins, William (2013). ''Between Raid and Rebellion: The Irish in Buffalo and Toronto, 1867\u20131916.'' Montreal: McGill-Queen's University.\n* Kenny, Kevin (2000). ''The American Irish: A History''. New York: Longman, 2000. {{ISBN|978-0582278172}}\n* McGee, Thomas D'Arcy (1852). [http://www.libraryireland.com/IrishSettlers/Contents.php ''A History of the Irish Settlers in North America from the Earliest Period to the Census of 1850'']\n* Meagher, Timothy J. (2005). ''The Columbia Guide to Irish American History''. New York: Columbia University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-231-12070-8}}\n* Merryweather (n\u00e9e Green), Kath (2009). ''The Irish Rossiter: Ancestors and Their World Wide Descendents and Connections''. Bristol, UK: Irishancestors4u. {{ISBN|978-0-9562976-0-0}}\n* Miller, Kerby M. (1985). ''Emigrants and Exiles: Ireland and the Irish Exodus to North America''. New York: Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|0-19-505187-4}}\n* Negra, Diane (ed.) (2006). ''The Irish in Us''. Durham, North Carolina: Duke University Press. {{ISBN|0-8223-3740-1}}\n* Quinlan, Kieran (2005). ''Strange Kin: Ireland and the American South''. Baton Rouge: Louisiana State University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-8071-2983-8}}\n* Quinlin, Michael P. (2004). ''Irish Boston: A Lively Look at Boston's Colorful Irish Past''. Gilford: Globe Pequot Press. {{ISBN|978-0-7627-2901-2}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Watson, William E. |author2=Eugene J. Halus,